\define ibox(image, caption, template:"Lightbox", btn-class:"ibox-btn", direct)
<$reveal type=match text="" default="$direct$"><$button class="$btn-class$"><$action-sendmessage $message="tm-modal" $param="$template$" image="$image$" caption="$caption$"/><$image source="$image$"/></$button></$reveal><$reveal type=nomatch text="" default="$direct$"><$button class="$btn-class$"><$action-sendmessage $message="tm-modal" $param="$image$"/><$image source="$image$"/></$button></$reveal><style>
.ibox-btn{
padding:5px;
}

.ibox-btn img{
width:150px;
}

.tc-modal .tc-modal-body > div > img{
 width:100%;
}
</style>
\end

        "$:/language/Help/fetch": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/fetch",
            "description": "Fetch tiddlers from wiki by URL",
            "text": "Fetch one or more files over HTTP/HTTPS, and import the tiddlers matching a filter, optionally transforming the incoming titles.\n\n```\n--fetch file <url> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch files <url-filter> <import-filter> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-file <url> <transform-filter>\n--fetch raw-files <url-filter> <transform-filter>\n```\n\nThe \"file\" and \"files\" variants fetch the specified files and attempt to import the tiddlers within them (the same processing as if the files were dragged into the browser window). The \"raw-file\" and \"raw-files\" variants fetch the specified files and then store the raw file data in tiddlers, without applying the import logic.\n\nWith the \"file\" and \"raw-file\" variants only a single file is fetched and the first parameter is the URL of the file to read.\n\nWith the \"files\" and \"raw-files\" variants, multiple files are fetched and the first parameter is a filter yielding a list of URLs of the files to read. For example, given a set of tiddlers tagged \"remote-server\" that have a field \"url\" the filter `[tag[remote-server]get[url]]` will retrieve all the available URLs.\n\nFor the \"file\" and \"files\" variants, the `<import-filter>` parameter specifies a filter determining which tiddlers are imported. It defaults to `[all[tiddlers]]` if not provided.\n\nFor all variants, the `<transform-filter>` parameter specifies an optional filter that transforms the titles of the imported tiddlers. For example, `[addprefix[$:/myimports/]]` would add the prefix `$:/myimports/` to each title.\n\nPreceding the `--fetch` command with `--verbose` will output progress information during the import.\n\nNote that TiddlyWiki will not fetch an older version of an already loaded plugin.\n\nThe following example retrieves all the non-system tiddlers from https://tiddlywiki.com and saves them to a JSON file:\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\" \"[!is[system]]\" \"\" --rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[!is[system]]\"\n```\n\nThe following example retrieves the \"favicon\" file from tiddlywiki.com and saves it in a file called \"output.ico\". Note that the intermediate tiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" is quoted in the \"--fetch\" command because it is being used as a transformation filter to replace the default title, while there are no quotes for the \"--savetiddler\" command because it is being used directly as a title.\n\n```\ntiddlywiki --verbose --fetch raw-file \"https://tiddlywiki.com/favicon.ico\" \"[[Icon Tiddler]]\" --savetiddler \"Icon Tiddler\" output.ico\n```\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/listen": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/listen",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "Serves a wiki over HTTP.\n\nThe listen command uses NamedCommandParameters:\n\n```\n--listen [<name>=<value>]...\n```\n\nAll parameters are optional with safe defaults, and can be specified in any order. The recognised parameters are:\n\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''credentials'' - pathname of credentials CSV file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''anon-username'' - the username for signing edits for anonymous users\n* ''username'' - optional username for basic authentication\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''authenticated-user-header'' - optional name of header to be used for trusted authentication\n* ''readers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to read from this wiki\n* ''writers'' - comma separated list of principals allowed to write to this wiki\n* ''csrf-disable'' - set to \"yes\" to disable CSRF checks (defaults to \"no\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''tls-cert'' - pathname of TLS certificate file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''tls-key'' - pathname of TLS key file (relative to wiki folder)\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nFor information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\n"
        },

        "$:/language/Help/render": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/render",
            "description": "Renders individual tiddlers to files",
            "text": "Render individual tiddlers identified by a filter and save the results to the specified files.\n\nOptionally, the title of a template tiddler can be specified. In this case, instead of directly rendering each tiddler, the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the title of the tiddler that is being rendered.\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--render <tiddler-filter> [<filename-filter>] [<render-type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\n* ''tiddler-filter'': A filter identifying the tiddler(s) to be rendered\n* ''filename-filter'': Optional filter transforming tiddler titles into pathnames. If omitted, defaults to `[is[tiddler]addsuffix[.html]]`, which uses the unchanged tiddler title as the filename\n* ''template'': Optional template through which each tiddler is rendered\n* ''render-type'': Optional render type: `text/html` (the default) returns the full HTML text and `text/plain` just returns the text content (ie it ignores HTML tags and other unprintable material)\n* ''name'': Name of optional variable\n* ''value'': Value of optional variable\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nNotes:\n\n* The output directory is not cleared of any existing files\n* Any missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n* When referring to a tiddler with spaces in its title, take care to use both the quotes required by your shell and also TiddlyWiki's double square brackets : `--render \"[[Motovun Jack.jpg]]\"`\n* The filename filter is evaluated with the selected items being set to the title of the tiddler currently being rendered, allowing the title to be used as the basis for computing the filename. For example `[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[static/]]` applies URI encoding to each title, and then adds the prefix `static/`\n* The `--render` command is a more flexible replacement for both the `--rendertiddler` and `--rendertiddlers` commands, which are deprecated\n\nExamples:\n\n* `--render \"[!is[system]]\" \"[encodeuricomponent[]addprefix[tiddlers/]addsuffix[.html]]\"` -- renders all non-system tiddlers as files in the subdirectory \"tiddlers\" with URL-encoded titles and the extension HTML\n\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/rendertiddler",
            "description": "Render an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType",
            "text": "(Note: The `--rendertiddler` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--render` command)\n\nRender an individual tiddler as a specified ContentType, defaulting to `text/html` and save it to the specified filename.\n\nOptionally the title of a template tiddler can be specified, in which case the template tiddler is rendered with the \"currentTiddler\" variable set to the tiddler that is being rendered (the first parameter value).\n\nA name and value for an additional variable may optionally also be specified.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler <title> <filename> [<type>] [<template>] [<name>] [<value>]\n```\n\nBy default, the filename is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny missing directories in the path to the filename are automatically created.\n\nFor example, the following command saves all tiddlers matching the filter `[tag[done]]` to a JSON file titled `output.json` by employing the core template `$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile`.\n\n```\n--rendertiddler \"$:/core/templates/exporters/JsonFile\" output.json text/plain \"\" exportFilter \"[tag[done]]\"\n```\n"

            "text": "(Note: The `--savetiddlers` command is deprecated in favour of the new, more flexible `--save` command)\n\nSaves a group of tiddlers in their raw text or binary format to the specified directory.\n\n```\n--savetiddlers <filter> <pathname> [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nThe output directory is cleared of existing files before saving the specified files. The deletion can be disabled by specifying the ''noclean'' flag.\n\nAny missing directories in the pathname are automatically created.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki (deprecated in favour of the new listen command)",
            "text": "Legacy command to serve a wiki over HTTP.\n\n```\n--server <port> <root-tiddler> <root-render-type> <root-serve-type> <username> <password> <host> <path-prefix> <debug-level>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number on which to listen; non-numeric values are interpreted as a system environment variable from which the port number is extracted (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''root-tiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''root-render-type'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''root-serve-type'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''path-prefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n* ''debug-level'' - optional debug level; set to \"debug\" to view request details (defaults to \"none\")\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation should only be used on a trusted network or over HTTPS.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password.\n\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nUsing an address like this exposes your system to the local network. For information on opening up your instance to the entire local network, and possible security concerns, see the WebServer tiddler at TiddlyWiki.com.\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port. It can be useful to use an environment variable to pass the port number to the Node.js process. This example references an environment variable called \"MY_PORT_NUMBER\":\n\n```\n--server MY_PORT_NUMBER $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n"
        },

the `PhotoGallery` macro. To use it first going to [[$:/plugins/OokTech/Photo Gallery/Edit Photo Gallery]] and click on `New Gallery`. Give the gallery a name and enter the filter you want to use the click `Create Gallery`. The gallery will contain any images returned by this filter.\n\nTo display the gallery in a tiddler use\n\n```\n<<PhotoGallery \"Gallery Name\">>\n```\n\nWhere `Gallery Name` is whatever you named your gallery when you created it. In the tiddler [[$:/plugins/OokTech/Photo Gallery/Edit Photo Gallery]] you can set the photo height when viewing the gallery as a list, this can be different for each gallery you create.\n\nCurrently when you set the order it is matched to the photo and affects all galleries that have that photo. I am working on allowing per-gallery ordering.\n\nYou can switch between viewing the gallery as a list of images or as one image at a time. You can switch the view mode using the buttons at the top of the gallery. If you click on an image in the gallery when viewing it as a list it will switch to single view mode on that image. In single view mode there are buttons at the top that let you page through the images in that gallery one by one. If an image has a caption field than the contents of the caption field are displayed above the image as well.\n"
        },
        "$:/plugins/OokTech/PhotoGallery/readme": {
            "title": "$:/plugins/OokTech/PhotoGallery/readme",
            "text": "To use this plugin you first create a photo gallery by using the tools in the [[edit photo gallery|$:/plugins/OokTech/Photo Gallery/Edit Photo Gallery]] tiddler. Click the `New Gallery` button and give the gallery a name and a filter. Tiddlers returned by the filter will be part of the gallery. You can then see the images that will be part of your gallery as well as give the images captions to be displayed in the gallery and to set the order of the images in the gallery.\n\nThen to display the photo gallery you have created put `<<PhotoGallery GalleryName>>` in your tiddler where you replace `GalleryName` with whatever name you gave your photo gallery.\n\nLicense: [[BSD 3 Clause|$:/plugins/OokTech/PhotoGallery/License]]\n\nCreator: [[OokTech|$:/plugins/OokTech/OokTechInfo]]\n\nSource: [[GitHub|https://https://github.com/OokTech/TW5-PhotoGallery]]\n"
        }

        "$:/language/Docs/Types/text/x-markdown": {

        "$:/plugins/tiddlywiki/markdown/markdown.js": {
            "text": "// Released under MIT license\n// Copyright (c) 2009-2010 Dominic Baggott\n// Copyright (c) 2009-2010 Ash Berlin\n// Copyright (c) 2011 Christoph Dorn <christoph@christophdorn.com> (http://www.christophdorn.com)\n\n/*jshint browser:true, devel:true */\n\n(function( expose ) {\n\n/**\n *  class Markdown\n *\n *  Markdown processing in Javascript done right. We have very particular views\n *  on what constitutes 'right' which include:\n *\n *  - produces well-formed HTML (this means that em and strong nesting is\n *    important)\n *\n *  - has an intermediate representation to allow processing of parsed data (We\n *    in fact have two, both as [JsonML]: a markdown tree and an HTML tree).\n *\n *  - is easily extensible to add new dialects without having to rewrite the\n *    entire parsing mechanics\n *\n *  - has a good test suite\n *\n *  This implementation fulfills all of these (except that the test suite could\n *  do with expanding to automatically run all the fixtures from other Markdown\n *  implementations.)\n *\n *  ##### Intermediate Representation\n *\n *  *TODO* Talk about this :) Its JsonML, but document the node names we use.\n *\n *  [JsonML]: http://jsonml.org/ \"JSON Markup Language\"\n **/\nvar Markdown = expose.Markdown = function(dialect) {\n  switch (typeof dialect) {\n    case \"undefined\":\n      this.dialect = Markdown.dialects.Gruber;\n      break;\n    case \"object\":\n      this.dialect = dialect;\n      break;\n    default:\n      if ( dialect in Markdown.dialects ) {\n        this.dialect = Markdown.dialects[dialect];\n      }\n      else {\n        throw new Error(\"Unknown Markdown dialect '\" + String(dialect) + \"'\");\n      }\n      break;\n  }\n  this.em_state = [];\n  this.strong_state = [];\n  this.debug_indent = \"\";\n};\n\n/**\n *  parse( markdown, [dialect] ) -> JsonML\n *  - markdown (String): markdown string to parse\n *  - dialect (String | Dialect): the dialect to use, defaults to gruber\n *\n *  Parse `markdown` and return a markdown document as a Markdown.JsonML tree.\n **/\nexpose.parse = function( source, dialect ) {\n  // dialect will default if undefined\n  var md = new Markdown( dialect );\n  return md.toTree( source );\n};\n\n/**\n *  toHTML( markdown, [dialect]  ) -> String\n *  toHTML( md_tree ) -> String\n *  - markdown (String): markdown string to parse\n *  - md_tree (Markdown.JsonML): parsed markdown tree\n *\n *  Take markdown (either as a string or as a JsonML tree) and run it through\n *  [[toHTMLTree]] then turn it into a well-formated HTML fragment.\n **/\nexpose.toHTML = function toHTML( source , dialect , options ) {\n  var input = expose.toHTMLTree( source , dialect , options );\n\n  return expose.renderJsonML( input );\n};\n\n/**\n *  toHTMLTree( markdown, [dialect] ) -> JsonML\n *  toHTMLTree( md_tree ) -> JsonML\n *  - markdown (String): markdown string to parse\n *  - dialect (String | Dialect): the dialect to use, defaults to gruber\n *  - md_tree (Markdown.JsonML): parsed markdown tree\n *\n *  Turn markdown into HTML, represented as a JsonML tree. If a string is given\n *  to this function, it is first parsed into a markdown tree by calling\n *  [[parse]].\n **/\nexpose.toHTMLTree = function toHTMLTree( input, dialect , options ) {\n  // convert string input to an MD tree\n  if ( typeof input ===\"string\" ) input = this.parse( input, dialect );\n\n  // Now convert the MD tree to an HTML tree\n\n  // remove references from the tree\n  var attrs = extract_attr( input ),\n      refs = {};\n\n  if ( attrs && attrs.references ) {\n    refs = attrs.references;\n  }\n\n  var html = convert_tree_to_html( input, refs , options );\n  merge_text_nodes( html );\n  return html;\n};\n\n// For Spidermonkey based engines\nfunction mk_block_toSource() {\n  return \"Markdown.mk_block( \" +\n          uneval(this.toString()) +\n          \", \" +\n          uneval(this.trailing) +\n          \", \" +\n          uneval(this.lineNumber) +\n          \" )\";\n}\n\n// node\nfunction mk_block_inspect() {\n  var util = require(\"util\");\n  return \"Markdown.mk_block( \" +\n          util.inspect(this.toString()) +\n          \", \" +\n          util.inspect(this.trailing) +\n          \", \" +\n          util.inspect(this.lineNumber) +\n          \" )\";\n\n}\n\nvar mk_block = Markdown.mk_block = function(block, trail, line) {\n  // Be helpful for default case in tests.\n  if ( arguments.length == 1 ) trail = \"\\n\\n\";\n\n  var s = new String(block);\n  s.trailing = trail;\n  // To make it clear its not just a string\n  s.inspect = mk_block_inspect;\n  s.toSource = mk_block_toSource;\n\n  if ( line != undefined )\n    s.lineNumber = line;\n\n  return s;\n};\n\nfunction count_lines( str ) {\n  var n = 0, i = -1;\n  while ( ( i = str.indexOf(\"\\n\", i + 1) ) !== -1 ) n++;\n  return n;\n}\n\n// Internal - split source into rough blocks\nMarkdown.prototype.split_blocks = function splitBlocks( input, startLine ) {\n  input = input.replace(/(\\r\\n|\\n|\\r)/g, \"\\n\");\n  // [\\s\\S] matches _anything_ (newline or space)\n  // [^] is equivalent but doesn't work in IEs.\n  var re = /([\\s\\S]+?)($|\\n#|\\n(?:\\s*\\n|$)+)/g,\n      blocks = [],\n      m;\n\n  var line_no = 1;\n\n  if ( ( m = /^(\\s*\\n)/.exec(input) ) != null ) {\n    // skip (but count) leading blank lines\n    line_no += count_lines( m[0] );\n    re.lastIndex = m[0].length;\n  }\n\n  while ( ( m = re.exec(input) ) !== null ) {\n    if (m[2] == \"\\n#\") {\n      m[2] = \"\\n\";\n      re.lastIndex--;\n    }\n    blocks.push( mk_block( m[1], m[2], line_no ) );\n    line_no += count_lines( m[0] );\n  }\n\n  return blocks;\n};\n\n/**\n *  Markdown#processBlock( block, next ) -> undefined | [ JsonML, ... ]\n *  - block (String): the block to process\n *  - next (Array): the following blocks\n *\n * Process `block` and return an array of JsonML nodes representing `block`.\n *\n * It does this by asking each block level function in the dialect to process\n * the block until one can. Succesful handling is indicated by returning an\n * array (with zero or more JsonML nodes), failure by a false value.\n *\n * Blocks handlers are responsible for calling [[Markdown#processInline]]\n * themselves as appropriate.\n *\n * If the blocks were split incorrectly or adjacent blocks need collapsing you\n * can adjust `next` in place using shift/splice etc.\n *\n * If any of this default behaviour is not right for the dialect, you can\n * define a `__call__` method on the dialect that will get invoked to handle\n * the block processing.\n */\nMarkdown.prototype.processBlock = function processBlock( block, next ) {\n  var cbs = this.dialect.block,\n      ord = cbs.__order__;\n\n  if ( \"__call__\" in cbs ) {\n    return cbs.__call__.call(this, block, next);\n  }\n\n  for ( var i = 0; i < ord.length; i++ ) {\n    //D:this.debug( \"Testing\", ord[i] );\n    var res = cbs[ ord[i] ].call( this, block, next );\n    if ( res ) {\n      //D:this.debug(\"  matched\");\n      if ( !isArray(res) || ( res.length > 0 && !( isArray(res[0]) ) ) )\n        this.debug(ord[i], \"didn't return a proper array\");\n      //D:this.debug( \"\" );\n      return res;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Uhoh! no match! Should we throw an error?\n  return [];\n};\n\nMarkdown.prototype.processInline = function processInline( block ) {\n  return this.dialect.inline.__call__.call( this, String( block ) );\n};\n\n/**\n *  Markdown#toTree( source ) -> JsonML\n *  - source (String): markdown source to parse\n *\n *  Parse `source` into a JsonML tree representing the markdown document.\n **/\n// custom_tree means set this.tree to `custom_tree` and restore old value on return\nMarkdown.prototype.toTree = function toTree( source, custom_root ) {\n  var blocks = source instanceof Array ? source : this.split_blocks( source );\n\n  // Make tree a member variable so its easier to mess with in extensions\n  var old_tree = this.tree;\n  try {\n    this.tree = custom_root || this.tree || [ \"markdown\" ];\n\n    blocks:\n    while ( blocks.length ) {\n      var b = this.processBlock( blocks.shift(), blocks );\n\n      // Reference blocks and the like won't return any content\n      if ( !b.length ) continue blocks;\n\n      this.tree.push.apply( this.tree, b );\n    }\n    return this.tree;\n  }\n  finally {\n    if ( custom_root ) {\n      this.tree = old_tree;\n    }\n  }\n};\n\n// Noop by default\nMarkdown.prototype.debug = function () {\n  var args = Array.prototype.slice.call( arguments);\n  args.unshift(this.debug_indent);\n  if ( typeof print !== \"undefined\" )\n      print.apply( print, args );\n  if ( typeof console !== \"undefined\" && typeof console.log !== \"undefined\" )\n      console.log.apply( null, args );\n}\n\nMarkdown.prototype.loop_re_over_block = function( re, block, cb ) {\n  // Dont use /g regexps with this\n  var m,\n      b = block.valueOf();\n\n  while ( b.length && (m = re.exec(b) ) != null ) {\n    b = b.substr( m[0].length );\n    cb.call(this, m);\n  }\n  return b;\n};\n\n/**\n * Markdown.dialects\n *\n * Namespace of built-in dialects.\n **/\nMarkdown.dialects = {};\n\n/**\n * Markdown.dialects.Gruber\n *\n * The default dialect that follows the rules set out by John Gruber's\n * markdown.pl as closely as possible. Well actually we follow the behaviour of\n * that script which in some places is not exactly what the syntax web page\n * says.\n **/\nMarkdown.dialects.Gruber = {\n  block: {\n    atxHeader: function atxHeader( block, next ) {\n      var m = block.match( /^(#{1,6})\\s*(.*?)\\s*#*\\s*(?:\\n|$)/ );\n\n      if ( !m ) return undefined;\n\n      var header = [ \"header\", { level: m[ 1 ].length } ];\n      Array.prototype.push.apply(header, this.processInline(m[ 2 ]));\n\n      if ( m[0].length < block.length )\n        next.unshift( mk_block( block.substr( m[0].length ), block.trailing, block.lineNumber + 2 ) );\n\n      return [ header ];\n    },\n\n    setextHeader: function setextHeader( block, next ) {\n      var m = block.match( /^(.*)\\n([-=])\\2\\2+(?:\\n|$)/ );\n\n      if ( !m ) return undefined;\n\n      var level = ( m[ 2 ] === \"=\" ) ? 1 : 2;\n      var header = [ \"header\", { level : level }, m[ 1 ] ];\n\n      if ( m[0].length < block.length )\n        next.unshift( mk_block( block.substr( m[0].length ), block.trailing, block.lineNumber + 2 ) );\n\n      return [ header ];\n    },\n\n    code: function code( block, next ) {\n      // |    Foo\n      // |bar\n      // should be a code block followed by a paragraph. Fun\n      //\n      // There might also be adjacent code block to merge.\n\n      var ret = [],\n          re = /^(?: {0,3}\\t| {4})(.*)\\n?/,\n          lines;\n\n      // 4 spaces + content\n      if ( !block.match( re ) ) return undefined;\n\n      block_search:\n      do {\n        // Now pull out the rest of the lines\n        var b = this.loop_re_over_block(\n                  re, block.valueOf(), function( m ) { ret.push( m[1] ); } );\n\n        if ( b.length ) {\n          // Case alluded to in first comment. push it back on as a new block\n          next.unshift( mk_block(b, block.trailing) );\n          break block_search;\n        }\n        else if ( next.length ) {\n          // Check the next block - it might be code too\n          if ( !next[0].match( re ) ) break block_search;\n\n          // Pull how how many blanks lines follow - minus two to account for .join\n          ret.push ( block.trailing.replace(/[^\\n]/g, \"\").substring(2) );\n\n          block = next.shift();\n        }\n        else {\n          break block_search;\n        }\n      } while ( true );\n\n      return [ [ \"code_block\", ret.join(\"\\n\") ] ];\n    },\n\n    horizRule: function horizRule( block, next ) {\n      // this needs to find any hr in the block to handle abutting blocks\n      var m = block.match( /^(?:([\\s\\S]*?)\\n)?[ \\t]*([-_*])(?:[ \\t]*\\2){2,}[ \\t]*(?:\\n([\\s\\S]*))?$/ );\n\n      if ( !m ) {\n        return undefined;\n      }\n\n      var jsonml = [ [ \"hr\" ] ];\n\n      // if there's a leading abutting block, process it\n      if ( m[ 1 ] ) {\n        jsonml.unshift.apply( jsonml, this.processBlock( m[ 1 ], [] ) );\n      }\n\n      // if there's a trailing abutting block, stick it into next\n      if ( m[ 3 ] ) {\n        next.unshift( mk_block( m[ 3 ] ) );\n      }\n\n      return jsonml;\n    },\n\n    // There are two types of lists. Tight and loose. Tight lists have no whitespace\n    // between the items (and result in text just in the <li>) and loose lists,\n    // which have an empty line between list items, resulting in (one or more)\n    // paragraphs inside the <li>.\n    //\n    // There are all sorts weird edge cases about the original markdown.pl's\n    // handling of lists:\n    //\n    // * Nested lists are supposed to be indented by four chars per level. But\n    //   if they aren't, you can get a nested list by indenting by less than\n    //   four so long as the indent doesn't match an indent of an existing list\n    //   item in the 'nest stack'.\n    //\n    // * The type of the list (bullet or number) is controlled just by the\n    //    first item at the indent. Subsequent changes are ignored unless they\n    //    are for nested lists\n    //\n    lists: (function( ) {\n      // Use a closure to hide a few variables.\n      var any_list = \"[*+-]|\\\\d+\\\\.\",\n          bullet_list = /[*+-]/,\n          number_list = /\\d+\\./,\n          // Capture leading indent as it matters for determining nested lists.\n          is_list_re = new RegExp( \"^( {0,3})(\" + any_list + \")[ \\t]+\" ),\n          indent_re = \"(?: {0,3}\\\\t| {4})\";\n\n      // TODO: Cache this regexp for certain depths.\n      // Create a regexp suitable for matching an li for a given stack depth\n      function regex_for_depth( depth ) {\n\n        return new RegExp(\n          // m[1] = indent, m[2] = list_type\n          \"(?:^(\" + indent_re + \"{0,\" + depth + \"} {0,3})(\" + any_list + \")\\\\s+)|\" +\n          // m[3] = cont\n          \"(^\" + indent_re + \"{0,\" + (depth-1) + \"}[ ]{0,4})\"\n        );\n      }\n      function expand_tab( input ) {\n        return input.replace( / {0,3}\\t/g, \"    \" );\n      }\n\n      // Add inline content `inline` to `li`. inline comes from processInline\n      // so is an array of content\n      function add(li, loose, inline, nl) {\n        if ( loose ) {\n          li.push( [ \"para\" ].concat(inline) );\n          return;\n        }\n        // Hmmm, should this be any block level element or just paras?\n        var add_to = li[li.length -1] instanceof Array && li[li.length - 1][0] == \"para\"\n                   ? li[li.length -1]\n                   : li;\n\n        // If there is already some content in this list, add the new line in\n        if ( nl && li.length > 1 ) inline.unshift(nl);\n\n        for ( var i = 0; i < inline.length; i++ ) {\n          var what = inline[i],\n              is_str = typeof what == \"string\";\n          if ( is_str && add_to.length > 1 && typeof add_to[add_to.length-1] == \"string\" ) {\n            add_to[ add_to.length-1 ] += what;\n          }\n          else {\n            add_to.push( what );\n          }\n        }\n      }\n\n      // contained means have an indent greater than the current one. On\n      // *every* line in the block\n      function get_contained_blocks( depth, blocks ) {\n\n        var re = new RegExp( \"^(\" + indent_re + \"{\" + depth + \"}.*?\\\\n?)*$\" ),\n            replace = new RegExp(\"^\" + indent_re + \"{\" + depth + \"}\", \"gm\"),\n            ret = [];\n\n        while ( blocks.length > 0 ) {\n          if ( re.exec( blocks[0] ) ) {\n            var b = blocks.shift(),\n                // Now remove that indent\n                x = b.replace( replace, \"\");\n\n            ret.push( mk_block( x, b.trailing, b.lineNumber ) );\n          }\n          else {\n            break;\n          }\n        }\n        return ret;\n      }\n\n      // passed to stack.forEach to turn list items up the stack into paras\n      function paragraphify(s, i, stack) {\n        var list = s.list;\n        var last_li = list[list.length-1];\n\n        if ( last_li[1] instanceof Array && last_li[1][0] == \"para\" ) {\n          return;\n        }\n        if ( i + 1 == stack.length ) {\n          // Last stack frame\n          // Keep the same array, but replace the contents\n          last_li.push( [\"para\"].concat( last_li.splice(1, last_li.length - 1) ) );\n        }\n        else {\n          var sublist = last_li.pop();\n          last_li.push( [\"para\"].concat( last_li.splice(1, last_li.length - 1) ), sublist );\n        }\n      }\n\n      // The matcher function\n      return function( block, next ) {\n        var m = block.match( is_list_re );\n        if ( !m ) return undefined;\n\n        function make_list( m ) {\n          var list = bullet_list.exec( m[2] )\n                   ? [\"bulletlist\"]\n                   : [\"numberlist\"];\n\n          stack.push( { list: list, indent: m[1] } );\n          return list;\n        }\n\n\n        var stack = [], // Stack of lists for nesting.\n            list = make_list( m ),\n            last_li,\n            loose = false,\n            ret = [ stack[0].list ],\n            i;\n\n        // Loop to search over block looking for inner block elements and loose lists\n        loose_search:\n        while ( true ) {\n          // Split into lines preserving new lines at end of line\n          var lines = block.split( /(?=\\n)/ );\n\n          // We have to grab all lines for a li and call processInline on them\n          // once as there are some inline things that can span lines.\n          var li_accumulate = \"\";\n\n          // Loop over the lines in this block looking for tight lists.\n          tight_search:\n          for ( var line_no = 0; line_no < lines.length; line_no++ ) {\n            var nl = \"\",\n                l = lines[line_no].replace(/^\\n/, function(n) { nl = n; return \"\"; });\n\n            // TODO: really should cache this\n            var line_re = regex_for_depth( stack.length );\n\n            m = l.match( line_re );\n            //print( \"line:\", uneval(l), \"\\nline match:\", uneval(m) );\n\n            // We have a list item\n            if ( m[1] !== undefined ) {\n              // Process the previous list item, if any\n              if ( li_accumulate.length ) {\n                add( last_li, loose, this.processInline( li_accumulate ), nl );\n                // Loose mode will have been dealt with. Reset it\n                loose = false;\n                li_accumulate = \"\";\n              }\n\n              m[1] = expand_tab( m[1] );\n              var wanted_depth = Math.floor(m[1].length/4)+1;\n              //print( \"want:\", wanted_depth, \"stack:\", stack.length);\n              if ( wanted_depth > stack.length ) {\n                // Deep enough for a nested list outright\n                //print ( \"new nested list\" );\n                list = make_list( m );\n                last_li.push( list );\n                last_li = list[1] = [ \"listitem\" ];\n              }\n              else {\n                // We aren't deep enough to be strictly a new level. This is\n                // where Md.pl goes nuts. If the indent matches a level in the\n                // stack, put it there, else put it one deeper then the\n                // wanted_depth deserves.\n                var found = false;\n                for ( i = 0; i < stack.length; i++ ) {\n                  if ( stack[ i ].indent != m[1] ) continue;\n                  list = stack[ i ].list;\n                  stack.splice( i+1, stack.length - (i+1) );\n                  found = true;\n                  break;\n                }\n\n                if (!found) {\n                  //print(\"not found. l:\", uneval(l));\n                  wanted_depth++;\n                  if ( wanted_depth <= stack.length ) {\n                    stack.splice(wanted_depth, stack.length - wanted_depth);\n                    //print(\"Desired depth now\", wanted_depth, \"stack:\", stack.length);\n                    list = stack[wanted_depth-1].list;\n                    //print(\"list:\", uneval(list) );\n                  }\n                  else {\n                    //print (\"made new stack for messy indent\");\n                    list = make_list(m);\n                    last_li.push(list);\n                  }\n                }\n\n                //print( uneval(list), \"last\", list === stack[stack.length-1].list );\n                last_li = [ \"listitem\" ];\n                list.push(last_li);\n              } // end depth of shenegains\n              nl = \"\";\n            }\n\n            // Add content\n            if ( l.length > m[0].length ) {\n              li_accumulate += nl + l.substr( m[0].length );\n            }\n          } // tight_search\n\n          if ( li_accumulate.length ) {\n            add( last_li, loose, this.processInline( li_accumulate ), nl );\n            // Loose mode will have been dealt with. Reset it\n            loose = false;\n            li_accumulate = \"\";\n          }\n\n          // Look at the next block - we might have a loose list.             "text": "! Markdown Dialects\n\nBy default the markdown parser recognises the original dialect of Markdown [[as described by John Gruber|http://daringfireball.net/projects/markdown/]]. An extended dialect called \"Maruku\" is also included that provides table support and other advanced features. The syntax extensions are modelled on those of [[PHP Markdown Extra|https://michelf.ca/projects/php-markdown/extra/]].\n\nThe configuration tiddler [[$:/config/markdown/dialect]] determines which dialect is used:\n\n|!Dialect |!Description |\n|Gruber |Standard Markdown |\n|Maruku |Extended Maruku Markdown |\n\n\n! Creating ~WikiLinks\n\nCreate wiki links with the usual Markdown link syntax targeting `#` and the target tiddler title:\n\n```\n[link text](#TiddlerTitle)\n```\n\n! Images\n\nMarkdown image syntax can be used to reference images by tiddler title or an external URI. For example:\n\n```\n![alt text](/path/to/img.jpg \"Title\")\n\n![alt text](Motovun Jack.jpg \"Title\")\n```\n"

Or 12 months

''Milestones:''

Key behaviors according to the CDC are bolded.

* Basics:
** ''Uses simple gestures like shaking head no or waving bye-bye''
** ''Says "Mama" and "Dada" and simple exclamations like "Uh-oh!"''
** ''Responds to simple spoken requests''
* Social:
**  ''Plays games like peekaboo and patty-cake''
** Is shy or nervous around strangers
** Cries when mom or dad leaves
** Has favorite things and people
** Shows fear in some situations
** Hands you a book when they want to hear a story
** Repeats sounds or actions to get your attention
** Puts out arm or leg to help with dressing







Or 1.5 years

''Milestones:''

Key behaviors according to the CDC are bolded.

* Basics:
** ''Point to show others something interesting''
** ''Say several single words''
* Social:
** ''Likes to hand things to others as play''
** ''Plays simple pretend, such as feeding a doll''
** May have temper tantrums
** May be afraid of strangers
** Shows affection to familiar people
** May cling to caregivers in new situations
** Points to show others something interesting (joint attention)
** Explores alone, but with parents close by






Or 24 months

''Milestones:''

Key behaviors according to the CDC are bolded.

* Language:
** ''Points to things or pictures when they are named''
** ''Say simple simple sentences with two to four words''
** ''Follow simple instructions''
** Knows names of familiar people and body parts
** Repeats words overheard in conversation
** Points to things in a book
* Motor:
** Stands on tiptoe
** Kicks a ball
** Begins to run
** Walks up and down stairs by holding onto rail
** Climbs furniture without help
** Throws ball overhand
** Makes or copies straight lines and circles
* Cognitive:
** Finds things even when hidden under two to three covers
** Begins to sort shapes and colors
** Completes sentences and rhymes in familiar books
** Plays simple make-believe games
** Builds towers of four or more blocks
** Might use one hand more than the other
** Follows two-step instructions such as "Pick up your shoe and put it in the closet."
** Names items in a picture book such as a cat, bird, or dog
* Social:
**  ''Gets excited when with other children''
** Copies others, especially adults and older children
** Shows more and more independence
** Shows defiant behavior (doing what told not to do)
** Plays mainly beside other children, but is beginning to include other children, such as in chase games
* Play Skills:
** Uses objects symbolically, such a a crayon as a bottle for a doll
** Uses toys a complete objects without becoming preoccupied with just one part






Means of prioritizing your top priority work:

# Dying - issues related to acute patient safety
# Diagnosis - issues relating to identifying the pathology
# Discharge - getting patients out in a timely manner

''Omphalocele:''

Abdominal contents are at midline with sac covering them

''Gastroschisis:''

Abdominal contents are lateral without covering membrane

''Treatment:''

In either case is silo that slowly forces contents back into the abdomen over time

''Pathophysiology:''

100's-1000's of seizures per day

Technically a type of generalized seizure

''Presentation:''

* Loss of consciousness present
* No loss of tone
* No post-ictal state
* Sometimes misdiagnosed as [[ADHD]]

''Diagnosis:''

EEG

''Treatment:''

Ethosuximide

''Follow-up:''

To see if child outgrows them






''Pathophysiology:''

Absence of myenteric plexus --> lower esophageal sphincter doesn't relax

''Presentation:''

* Dysphagia
* Knot/ball of food stuck at the GE junction

''Diagnosis:''

* Barium swallow = bird's beak sign
* Manometry = Absence of contraction in upper esophagus and persistent contraction in lower esophagus
* EGD with biopsy to rule out cancer

''Treatment:''

* Myotomy of lower esophageal sphincter
* Botulinum toxin only works temporarily
* Esophageal dilation carries perforation risk

''Follow-up:''

After myotomy for [[GERD]]






Aka Acute Coronary Syndrome






Great for promoting tummy time, reach, and roll in babies.

You don't need to buy an expensive product. Make your own!






Diarrhea lasting less than 4 weeks

''Defined by etiology:''

If watery, no fever, no leukocytosis, no fecal WBC's --> ''Enterotoxic:''

* [[C. diff]] associated with recent antibiotics
* [[ETEC]] associated with recent travel, especially to Central America
* [[Cholera]] associated with poorly sanitized water
* [[S. aureus]] associated with proteinaceous foods
* [[B. cereus]] associated with reheated rice
* [[Giardia]] associated with fresh water and camping

If bloody, febrile, leukocytosis, and fecal WBC's (lactoferrin more sensitive) --> ''Invasive:''

* [[EHEC]] (O157:H7) associated with uncooked meat and [[HUS]]
* [[Salmonella]] associated with eggs and poultry
* [[Shigella]] associated with HUS
* [[Campylobacter]] is most common invasive cause
* [[E. histolytica]] associated with HIV/AIDS

''Management:''

Red flags:

* Fever > 104
* Recently hospitalized
* Fecal blood or pus
* Electrolyte derangement
* Severe pain
* Immunocompromised
* Recent antibiotics
* Duration > 3 days

Could it be viral?:

* If patient has vomiting + diarrhea without red flags --> Viral gastroenteritis:
** Rehydrate (PO > IV)
** Loperamide
** Supportive watch and wait
* If patient has red flags --> Warrants investigation; Does the patient have C. diff?
** Patient has C. diff --> [[Treat|C. diff]]
** Patient does not have C. diff --> Check fecal WBC's and RBC's:
*** Positive fecal WBC's and RBC's --> Perform fecal culture and colonoscopy:
**** Positive fecal culture, negative colonoscopy --> Invasive Diarrhea; Treat with abx
**** Negative fecal culture, positive colonoscopy --> Early presentation of [[Chronic Diarrhea]]
*** Negative fecal WBC's and RBC's --> Enterotoxic; Perform fecal ova and parasites:
**** Positive O&P --> Treat for parasite
**** Negative O&P --> Other bacterial or viral cause; Treat empirically as appropriate






<<list-links "[tag[Acute Events in Infancy]]">>






''Pathophysiology:''

Acute [[HIV]] infection

''Presentation:''

Like the [[flu|Flu]], but tests for flu and similar diseases like mono are negative.

''Diagnosis:''

Nucleic acid amplification testing for viral load

''Treatment:''

Antiretroviral therapy in 2+1 configuration








A means of assessing how disorders affect a person's life. 

Such as with [[IDD]]:

* IQ > 70:
** Normal adaptive function
** Able to live independently, work some sort of job, and attend to [[ADL's|Activities of Daily Living]].
* IQ 50-70:
** Adaptive function of 6th-grader
** Able to work some sort of job and attend to ADL's
* IQ 35-49:
** Adaptive function of a 3rd grader
** Able to attend to ADL's
* IQ 20-34:
** Adaptive function of 3-year-old
** Unable to attend to ADL's without significant assistance
* IQ < 20:
** Adaptive function of infant
** ADL's severely impaired






Aka Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder

''Presentation:''

Impulsivity:

* Blurting answers
* Interruptions
* Fidgeting
* Cutting in line

Inattention:

* Talks fast
* Easily distracted
* Fails to complete tasks

Dependent on time and location:

* Presentation must be present in >= 2 settings
* Onset at age 7-12
* Duration greater than 6 months
* Symptoms are frequent

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Stimulants -- either methylphenidates or amphetamines are first line

Also special education and parent-training

''Follow-up:''

Include [[Absence Seizures]] on the ddx






This is a framework from the internal medicine perspective.

Mnemonic is ADC VANDALISM CCCC

''Admit'' to [Attending] [Needs]:

* Observation
* Med/Surg
* Medicine telemetry
* Specialized floors like ortho or L&D
* Step Down
* ICU

''Diagnosis'' in CMS language

''Condition:''

* Stable (Observation)
* Fair (General Floor)
* Guarded (ICU)
* Grim (ICU)

''Vitals:''

* q1hr for ICU
* q4hr for General floor
* q8hr/qShift for Skilled nursing facility
* qDay for Nursing home

''Activity:''

* Ad Lib (whatever they want)
* Advance as tolerated (Nursing assesses)
* No weight bearing
* Bed rest with bathroom privileges
* Bed rest (absolutely no leaving bed)

''Nursing'' instructions:

* Per routine (for that floor)
* Strict ins and outs
* Neuro checks [frequency]
* Weigh patient daily
* Etc

''Diet:''

* Advance as tolerated (nursing decides)
* Regular:
** Cardiac
** Diabetic
** Renal
* Soft mechanical
* Pureed
* Solid liquids
* Clears
* NPO x̅ meds
* NPO

''Allergies'' are either NKDA or [Class] [Reaction]

''Labs'' in format of [Test] [Frequency] [Time]:

* Default frequency is once
* Default time is now

''Imaging'' in format of [Test] [Indication]

''Special precautions'':

* Seizure
* Fall risk
* One-to-one

''Meds'' in format of [Medicine] [Dose] [Units] [Route] [Frequency]:

* Default next dose is next med pass
** If you want now --> Write "x1 now"
** If you need emergently --> Write "Stat", nursing is supposed to drop whatever else they are doing to complete this order

''Code Status:''

* Full
* DNR/DNI
* Comfort care only
* Modified (must be fully spelled out)

''Consult'' in format of [Name] or [Group] [Indication]

''Call MD'' with time range and number to reach you by

''Call MD if'' with rules:

* Sys BP >180 or <90
* Dia BP >110
* HR >120 or <50
* Temp >38 C

Aka ALD












Aka anti-epileptic drugs

* [[levetiracetam]] = Keppra
* [[phenytoin]] = Dilantin
* [[valproate]] = Depakote
* [[lamotrigine]]
* [[carbamazepine]]






''Pathophysiology:''

An [[HIV]]-infected person has AIDS when the CD4 count reaches below 200 or an [[opportunistic infection|Opportunistic Infection]] occurs

''Presentation:''

As an asymptomatic screen or with onset of opportunistic infection

''Diagnosis:''

Traditionally used ELISA test to screen and western blot for confirmation

Still ok to use ELISA for screen, but ''4th-generation assay'' is becoming new standard:

* Checks for HIV-1/2 antigen/antibody combination along with p24 antigen from HIV-1:
** If any are positive, reflexes to HIV-1 vs 2 antibody differentiation
** If negative, followed by nucleic acid amplification testing for HIV-1/2

''Treatment:''

Antiretroviral therapy with genotyping

Also screen for [[Gonorrhea]], [[Chlamydia]], [[Syphilis]], [[Toxoplasma]], [[Hepatitis B]], and [[Hepatitis C]]

* Abstain from alcohol
* Liver transplant

Two terms describing similar phenomena.

''ALTE:''

Aka Apparent Life-Threatening Event

Defined as caregiver comes to the provider concerned because of a change in color, tone, or breathing in infant.

* Most common:
** [[GERD]]
** Lower airway infection
** [[Seizure]] -- marked by abnormal eye movements or limb jerking
* Serious concerns:
** [[Sepsis]] --  change in temperature (high or low)
** Heart Disease -- [[Failure to Thrive]] and murmur
** [[Child Abuse]] -- multiple injuries

''BRUE:''

Aka Brief Resolved Unexplained Event

Defined as caregiver comes in concerned with infant less than 1 year old who experienced a change in color, tone, breathing, or responsiveness for less than 1 minute.

This definition more useful because it provides precise definition for diagnosis and triages next steps by risk:

* Low Risk --> Do nothing:
** Happening for the first time
** If term, age is greater than 60 days. If preemie, gestational age >= 32 weeks and post-conceptional age >=45 weeks.
** History and physical do not suggest any of the conditions listed in the differential above.
** No CPR was required.
* High Risk --> Monitor and investigate:
** Not low risk






''3 types:''

* [[Dementia]]:
** + Cognitive impairment
** + Memory loss
** Chronic and insidious
** Permanent
* Delirium:
** + Cognitive impairment
** + Memory loss
** Acute and overt 
** Waxes and wanes
* Amnesia:
** No cognitive impairment
** + Memory loss

Or Testicular Feminization

''Pathophysiology:''

Cells in person of X,Y genotype cannot properly respond to androgenic hormones

''Presentation:''

* [[Primary Amenorrhea]]
* Presence of secondary female sexual characteristics
* Presence of vulva, vagina, and clitoris on physical exam

''Diagnosis:''

* Ultrasound shows presence of gonads and absence of upper female reproductive tract
* Normal serum FSH/LH
* Increased testosterone
* Genotype is X,Y

''Treatment:''

* Option to surgically elevate the vagina
* After puberty has passed by around age 21, orchiectomy to prevent cancer

Acronym for appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respirations. Score as follows (with target of 7-10):

''0 Points:''

* Appearance = blue or pale
* Pulse = absent
* Grimace = absent
* Activity = absent
* Respirations = absent

''1 Point:''

* Appearance = in-between (acrocyanotic)
* Pulse < 100
* Grimace = with significant stimulation
* Activity = flexes but does not resist extension
* Respirations = irregular

''2 Points:''

* Appearance = pink
* Pulse > 100
* Grimace = with minimal stimulation
* Activity =  resists extension of limbs
* Respirations = strong and regular






Aka ABA

Most common therapy for [[ASD|Autism Spectrum Disorder]] involving positive reinforcement to teach adaptive behaviors.






''Pathophysiology:''

With portal hypertension, hydrostatic pressure exceeds oncotic pressure and pushes fluid into the belly

''Presentation:''

* Bulging flanks
* Shifting dullness
* Fluid wave

''Diagnosis:''

* Measure the serum-ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) to determine likely etiologies:
** If >= 1.1:
*** [[Cirrhosis]]
*** [[CHF]]
** If < 1.1:
*** [[Tuberculosis]]
*** [[Cancer|Hepatocellular Carcinoma]]
* Use paracentesis to evaluate for [[infection|SBP]]

''Treatment:''

* Furosemide
* Spironolactone
* Paracentesis






Aka Autism spectrum disorder

''Presentation:''

Impaired social communication in:

* Social reciprocity
* Social relationships
* Non-verbal communication
* Joint attention

Restricted/repetitive behaviors:

* Stereotyped or repetitive behaviors
* Need for routine and sameness
* Restricted interests
* Changes in sensory perception

Early warning signs:

* Lack of response to name
* Deficits in joint attention
* Inappropriate play with a toy
* Lack of pointing
* Intolerance of changes in routine and schedule
* Developmental/behavioral regression or plateauing, especially if motor milestones are preserved

Things to note on physical exam:

* Growth parameters
* Any dysmorphic features
* Motor stereotypies (e.g. hand flapping, toe walking)

''Differential:''

When warning signs present, think of:

* Developmental delay
* [[IDD]]
* [[Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder]]
* Genetic Syndromes:
** [[Fragile X Syndrome]]
** [[Tuberous Sclerosis]]
** [[Angelman Syndrome]]
** [[Rett Syndrome]]
* Hearing Impairment
* Mental Health Disorders:
** [[OCD]]
** [[Anxiety]]
** [[Depression]]
** [[ADHD]]
** [[ODD]]
** [[Tourette Syndrome]]
* Psychosocial Factors
* Sensory Issues
* Speech/language disorder

''Screening:''

Should occur with general pediatrician for all children at [[18 months]] and [[2 years]] or at any time if concern is raised by parent or pediatrician.

One of most widely used tools is the M-CHAT-R:

* Parent-completed questionnaire with follow-up interview
* Valid for 16-30 months age old children
* Workflow:
** If ''high-risk'' result --> ''Refer for comprehensive diagnostic evaluation, Early Intervention eligibility evaluation, audiologic evaluation, and continued follow-up in your clinic.''
** If medium risk --> Perform follow-up interview to determine if referral is still warranted
** If low-risk + provider and parent have no concerns --> Continue typical developmental surveillance

Important points to bring up if screen is positive:

* Screening is not diagnostic, it just tells us whether further evaluation is warranted
* Developmental issues are common in children
* Use specific examples for behaviors of concern
* Lots of potential interventions are available
* Intervening early leads to better outcomes
* Diagnosis is not meant to label, it is meant to ensure proper services


Regardless of screening results, these ''red flags'' necessitate further immediate evaluation:

* No babbling, pointing, or other gestures by [[1 year]].
* No single words by 16 months.
* No two-word spontaneous phrases by [[2 years]].
* Loss of language or social skills at any age.

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical, make appropriate rule-outs according to your differential.

DSM-V requires all criteria from social communication to be met and 2 of 4 from restricted, repetitive patterns. Symptoms must be present in early development, clinically significant in impairment, and not better explained by other condition.

Severity is assessed by degree of impairment and level of support needed.

A comprehensive evaluation will include a detailed history, physical exam, development/psychometric evaluation, ASD-specific tools.

''Treatment:''

Supportive with special education and social interaction training like [[ABA|Applied Behavior Analysis]].

Some adjunctive pharmacotherapy can be helpful.






When siblings know about and participate in the care of their terminally ill brothers or sisters, they cope better in the weeks leading up to the death and the months after.

Siblings should be included in discussions of care from the time of diagnosis, through death of the child, and beyond.

“Protecting” siblings by excluding them may cause long-term harm.

Siblings should be included in discussions about end-of-life care.

Siblings should be included in funeral planning.

Certain resources should be made available to support siblings through their grief and bereavement.

---

Spinetta JJ, Jankovic M, Eden T, et al. Guidelines for assistance to siblings of children with cancer: report of the SIOP working committee on psychosocial issues in pediatric oncology. Med Pediatr Oncol. 1999;33 :395– 398

''Presentation:''

Worsening jaundice at 2 weeks old with conjugated [[hyperbilirubinemia|Hyperbilirubinemia]].

''Diagnosis:''

Ultrasound will show absence of biliary ducts. Confirm with HIDA scan after 7 days of phenobarbital to stimulate bile ducts.

Serves as a means of excreting unwanted [[heme]] and also an [[antioxidant]]

Yellow in color

Lipid soluble; needs [[albumin]] to travel through bloodstream

Cytotoxic

Formed by successive action of [[heme oxygenase]] and [[biliverdin reductase]]

''Conjugation comparison:''

*Unconjugated:
** Water soluble
** Excreted in the urine
** Turns urine dark
** Does not cross blood brain barrier (BBB)
** Does not cause [[kernicterus|Kernicterus]]
*Conjugated:
**Fat soluble
**Not excreted in the urine (to significant degree)
** Doesn't turn urine dark
** Does cross BBB
** Does cause kernicterus






Aka BIND

Spectrum of neurotoxicity going from acute bilirubin encephalopathy to kernicterus all involving some disorder in vision, hearing, and later gait, speech, and cognition.

Be especially concerned when bilirubin levels rise above 25.

Acute bilirubin encephalopathy starts subtly. The neonate may be sleepy but hypotonic or have a high-pitched cry; he maybe irritable or inconsolable, jittery or lethargic.

The dehydration and neurologic dysfunction from hyperbilirubinemia may even cause fever.  Check the bilirubin in any neonate you are working up for [[sepsis|Sepsis]].

Acute bilirubin encephalopathy may progress to an abnormal neurologic exam, seizures, apnea, or coma.

Kernicterus is the final, permanent result of bilirubin encephalpathy. The child may have choreoathetoid cerebral palsy with chorea, tremor, ballismus, and dystonia. He may have sensorineural hearing loss, or cognitive dysfunction.






Aka Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo

''Pathophysiology:''

Otolith in the semicircular canals

''Presentation:''

Recurrent, reproducible vertigo that lasts < 1 minute.

''Diagnosis:''

Dix-Hallpike shows rotary nystagmus

''Treatment:''

Epley Maneuver













''Signs:''

Fever and a headache

Photophobia and phonophobia

+/- Nausea and vomiting

''Differential Diagnosis for Fever and Headache plus Signs:''

* Systemic illness
* [[Meningitis]] (suggested by stiff neck)
* [[Brain Abscess]] (suggested by focal neurological deficits)
** Rule out cancer
* [[Encephalitis]] (suggested by altered mental status)

''Clinical Algorithm aka "So you have fever and a headache":''

Is a lumbar puncture (LP) safe aka is there increased intracranial pressure?:

* Evaluate by means of [[FAILS]] mnemonic:
** Focal neurological deficits, [[Altered Mental Status]], Immunocompromised, Lesion over site of proposed puncture, Seizures
* FAILS positive, LP is unsafe --> First, give empiric antibiotics (abx), then do brain CT looking for space-occupying lesion:
** Mass lesion is present --> Do they have AIDS and/or are they [[Toxoplasma]] Ab-positive?
*** AIDS-positive/Toxoplasma Ab-positive --> Treat and rescan in six weeks.
*** No toxo, or scan still positive after treatment --> Brain biopsy:
**** Biopsy shows cancer --> Chemotherapy and radiation
**** Biopsy shows abscess --> Drain and give abx
**Mass lesion is not present --> Proceed to LP:
* FAILS negative, LP is safe --> Do LP:
** LP shows 1000's of PMN's--> Bacterial meningitis, give empiric abx coverage.
** LP does //not// show 1000's of PMN's--> Work up for atypicals based on presentation:
*** Work-up shows [[Tb|Tuberculosis]] --> [[RIPE]] therapy
*** Work-up shows [[Lyme|Lyme Disease]] or [[RMSF]] --> Ceftriaxone
*** Work-up shows [[Cryptococcus|Cryptococcal Meningitis]] --> Amphotericin B
**LP shows lymphocytes and clinical picture suggests altered mental status --> Encephalitis, check NAAT for HSV
*** NAAT is HSV-positive --> Give acyclovir
*** NAAT is HSV-negative --> Supportive care

Aka Breast Feeding Jaundice and Breast Milk Jaundice

''Comparison:''

*Feeding:
**Usually happens at age less than 7 days
**Issue of quantity
**Baby isn't getting fed enough so bowel movements are decreased --> More reabsorption of bilirubin
**Bilirubin largely unconjugated
**Treatment is to feed more
*Milk:
**Usually happens at age greater than 7 days
**Some component of milk inhibits conjugation of bilirubin --> Decreased excretion
**Bilirubin largely unconjugated
**Treatment is to feed hydrolyzed formula

Premature infant with increased O2 demands for greater than 28 days

CXR = ground-glass opacities in the lungs

''Treatment:''

* Support with increased FiO2
* Prenatal = steroids
* Postnatal = surfactant

''Follow-up:''

Diffuse parenchymal lung disease






''Parkland Formula for Children:''

(%BSA of anywhere with 2nd or 3rd degree burn) * 4 * (kg of body weight) = Amount of fluids needed in first 24 hours to maintain hemodynamic stability

Give 50% of that fluid in the first 8 hours and the rest in the next 16 hours.

Body surface area is approximated as:

* 18% for front and back of head
* 9% for each arm
* 9% for each leg
* 9% for both feet
* 9% for chest 
* 9% for abdomen
* 18% for back
* 1 % for genitals

NAAT

''Treatment:''

If mild:

* 1st time --> PO metronidazole
* 2nd time --> PO MTZ
* 3rd time --> fidaxomicin
* Refractory --> fecal transplant

If severe --> IV MTZ + PO Vancomycin






General rule: Call a consult when you need something done, not when you need help with the medicine.

''Beforehand:''

* Clarify your question
* Acquire the identifying info -- Name, DOB, room number, MRN 
* Have your data tracker already filled out
* Inform the patient a consultant will be visiting them

''The Page:''

* Do not text them unless you already have a close relationship
* Make the return number to your cell phone (not your pager) -or- remain near the landline number for 5 minutes

''When they return the call:''

* Talk slowly and clear
* Give your name (1st name), rank, and specialty
* Address them as Dr. Last-name (out of respect)
* ID the patient
* State the reason for the consult
* Brief hx (don't tell them what to do at the end, e.g. we need you to do this procedure)
* Be ready to answer questions

''Timing:''

* Emergent (stat)
* Urgent (should be done in 12 hours)
* Routine (24 hours)
** Don't place call in middle of the night
** Call in early morning and early in admission

''After:''

* Read their note
* Talk to them if they're that kind of person or you need to clarify something
* Acknowledge recommendations in your next note and explain why you are or are not following them

''Pathophysiology:''

Infection of the subcutaneous tissue, usually by //Staphylococcus// or Group A //Streptococcus//.

''Presentation:''

Red, hot, tender area of well-demarcated skin with portal of entry for infection.

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical.

Do not culture unless you can swab a pocket of pus because too much cross-contamination from skin flora.

Abscess formation is suggestive of //Staph//.

''Treatment:''

Try to mark borders of infection with pen before you initiate treatment!

If non-toxic:

* Suggestive of //Strep// --> 1st generation cephalosporin
* Suggestive of //Staph// --> Bactrim

If toxic:

* Suggestive of //Strep// --> [[Unasyn]] or [[Zosyn]]
* Suggetive of //Staph// --> vancomycin or linezolid or clindamycin

If patient is diabetic with foot ulcer, there is risk for polymicrobial superinfection --> broad-spectrum abx

''Follow-up:''

For [[Osteomyelitis]] if infection recurs or fails to improve with appropriate treatment

!! Pathophys:

Type I: Herniation of the cerebellar tonsils

Type II: Larger cerebellar vermian displacement

[img[chiarimalformation.jpg]]

!! Presentation:

Pain areas:  in the neck, headache exacerbated by valsalva

Muscular: muscle weakness, problems with coordination, stiff muscles, or overactive reflexes

Sensory: pins and needles, reduced sensation of touch, or uncomfortable tingling and burning

Visual: blurred vision, double vision, or sensitivity to light

Also common: difficulty swallowing, nausea, rapid involuntary eye movement, ringing in the ears, vertigo, or impaired voice

Or varicella

''Pathophysiology:''

Caused by [[Varicella Zoster Virus]]

''Presentation:''

No fever. Rash will be diffuse vesicles on erythematous bases in different stages of healing.

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Supportive

''Prophylaxis:''

Prevent with the [[MMRV]] vaccine. You should no longer take kids to "pox parties". Better to prevent infection so as to not get shingles in later life from reactivation of virus.

''Follow-up:''

Can later cause [[Shingles]]






Abuse is defined as positive to active, intentional harm

Neglect is negative symptoms due to passive, absence of support

''Risk Factors:''

Child-related -- Any kind of disability (physical, cognitiv, intellectual), or prematurity

Parent-related -- Personal history of abuse, single parent, young, low socioeconomic status, non-biological parent

''Presentation:''

Child-related:

* Not crying in presence of parent in scenario when you would expect it
* Running away from parent
* Seeks comfort from provider

Injury-related:

* Fractures -- femur or skull
* Bruises:
** Different stages of healing
** Buttocks or lower back
** Inappropriate to age
** [[Subdural Hematoma]]
* Burns:
** Dunking burns on feet or buttocks
** Cigarette burns are punctuate and circular
* Sexual:
** Any STD in younger child
** Anal/vaginal trauma

''Responsibilities:''

* Report if there is any suspicion to appropriate agency. Best to inform family that you are reporting in order to maintain alliance.
* Top-priority is child safety. May need to separate child from abuser with hospitalization as last resort.
* Help with coping. Redirect the stress of the abuser. Goal is to keep families together if possible.






2 months -- Child should be able to lift head, make some noises, and give a social smile (Februrary, Valentine's Day, lift your head for a kiss and smile)

4 months -- Child should be able to roll over and make some noises (April Fool's, roll over laughing)

[[6 months]] -- Child should be able to sit up, make some noise, and get stranger anxiety (Fourth of July, sit up for fireworks and get anxious with Mom's friends trying to pinch your cheeks)

[[1 year]] -- Child should be able to walk, speak 1-word sentences, and feel separation anxiety (December, Xmas, child walks up to Santa, says hi, and feels anxious as Mom waits at the line)

[[18 months]]

[[2 years]] -- Child should be able to take stairs and speak in 2 word sentences.

[[3 years]] -- Child should be able to ride tricycle, draw circle, and speak 3-word sentences.

[[4 years]] -- Child should be able to hop, draw cross, and speak 4-word sentences.

5 years -- Child should be able to skip, draw triangle, and speak 5-word sentences.

''Pathophysiology:''

* Stagnant bile in the obstructed bile duct gets infected with gut flora:
** Gram-negative rods
** Anaerobes

''Presentation:''

Charcot's Triad:

* RUQ pain
* [[Jaundice]]
* Fever

Plus Reynold's Pentad:

* [[Hypotension]]
* [[Altered Mental Status]]

''Diagnosis:''

* RUQ U/S = obstruction
* Don't waste time on other tests in this emergent situation

''Treatment:''

* NPO, IVF, Abx --> Emergent ERCP --> Urgent cholecystectomy






''Pathophysiology:''

Gall stones in the cystic duct leading to gall bladder inflammation:

* Pericholecystic fluid
* Thickened gall bladder wall
* Gall stones

''Presentation:''

* //Constant// RUQ pain
* Positive Murphy's sign
* Fever and leukocytosis

''Diagnosis:''

* RUQ U/S shows inflammatory signs listed above
* If U/S negative, but still suspicious, HIDA scan = no filling of gall bladder

''Treatment:''

* NPO, IVF, Abx --> Urgent cholecystectomy
* If not surgical candidate --> Cholecystostomy 






''Pathophysiology:''

* Gall stone lodges in the common bile duct
* +/- [[Hepatitis]]
* +/- [[Pancreatitis]]
* Obstructive [[Jaundice]]

''Presentation:''

* Painful jaundice
* Positive Murphy's Sign
* Fever and leukocytosis
* May observe "Ball-Valve" effect  with waxing and waning pain

''Diagnosis:''

* RUQ U/S shows obstruction with dilation of the CBD
* MRCP if you need confirmation

''Treatment:''

* NPO, IVF, Abx --> Urgent ERCP --> Elective Cholecystectomy






Or gall stones

''Pathophysiology:''

Formed from a mix of cholesterol (green) and hemolytic pigment (black)

''Presentation:''

* Classically female, forty, fat, and fertile.
* Colicky RUQ pain radiating up to shoulder.
* Worse with fatty meals.

''Diagnosis:''

RUQ U/S = gall stones

''Treatment:''

* Elective cholecystectomy
* If not surgical candidate --> ursodeoxycholic acid







Diarrhea lasting greater than a month

''Categories:''

* Secretory - No change in around meals and symptoms present at night
* Osmotic - Symptoms worse after meals, but no symptoms at night. [[Osmolar Gap]] present. Fecal fats present if [[malabsorptive subtype|Malabsorption]].
* Inflammatory - Fecal WBC's, RBC's, and mucous present.

''The "Usual Suspects:''

* Laxatives
* Medications
* Lactose Intolerance
* [[C. diff]]
* [[Celiac Sprue]]

''Work-up:''

Check the usual suspects:

* If none of the usual suspects fit --> Check fecal WBC's, RBC's, fat content, osms as well as trial NPO:
** If no abnormal labs, no change with NPO, and sxs present at night --> Secretory pattern; Check for hormone imbalances and C. diff as well as perform EGD with biopsy
** If osmolar gap present +/- fecal fat and sxs worse with meals but no nocturnal sxs --> Osmotic pattern; Review H&P, perform EGD with bx and disease-specific work-ups
** If fecal WBC's/RBC's present --> Inflammatory pattern; Perform colonoscopy

''See also:''

* [[VIPoma]]
* [[Carcinoid syndrome]]
* [[Gastrinoma]]







''Etiologies:''

* [[Viral Hepatitis]]
* [[Wilson's disease]]
* [[Hemochromatosis]]
* [[Alpha 1-Antitrypsin Deficiency]]
* [[PSC]]
* [[PBC]]
* [[Alcoholic Hepatitis]]
* [[NASH]]

''Complications:''

* [[Hepatic Encephalopathy]]
* Elevated estrogen:
** Gynecomastia
** Palmar erythema
** Spider angiomata
* Portal Hypertension:
** Thrombocytopenia (due to splenic sequestration)
** [[Ascites]]:
*** [[SBP]]
** [[Varices]]
* Jaundice (from elevated bilirubin)
* Pruritis (from elevated bile salts)
* Decrease in albumin production
* Decrease in factors 2, 7, 9, and 10 --> elevated INR and bleeding risk
* [[Hepatocellular Carcinoma]]






''Pathophys:''

Failure of growth and/or fusion of the hard palate/soft palate/lips. Can be unilateral, bilateral, or medial.

''Presentation:''

Sometimes just a cosmetic issue, but can cause poor latch leading to [[failure to thrive|Failure to Thrive]]. Also if deep structures are involved, can lead to recurrent infections.

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Surgical correction:

* Lips at 11-12 weeks
* Palate at 11-12 months

''Pathophysiology:''

Vascular

''Presentation:''

Asymptomatic for months, then a cluster of attacks:

* 8-10 per day
* With unilateral eye pain
* And Horner-like syndrome

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

# 100% O2
# Triptan

''Prophylaxis:''

With calcium channel blocker like verapamil

''Follow-up:''

With brain MRI just to make sure this isn't a secondary headache etiology






Aka CBT

''Follow-Up:''

Good way to assess whether patient is getting proper therapy is asking whether they've been getting homework from their therapist.






We do not know for sure what causes colic. It may be related to gassiness.

Any bottle claiming to prevent colic is false advertising, but they can reduce the amount of ingested air --> reducing gas.

Gripe water (fennel and ginger) is not proven to prevent colic, but anecdotally helps some kids and fairly harmless.

Simethicone products are effective at reducing gas.







<<list-links "[tag[Colon]]">>






Or colon cancer

''Pathophysiology:''

Lesions develop typically in people greater than 50 yo secondary to inflammation and genetics

Risk factors:

* Smoking
* Ethanol
* Processed/red meat
* High BMI

"Good" lesions are small, pedunculated, and tubular

"Bad" lesions are large, sessile, and villous

''Presentation:''

Best to worse prognosis:

# On asymptomatic screen
# With iron-deficiency anemia in man or post-menopausal woman
# Grossly symptomatic:
#* Change in caliber of stool to pencil-thin
#* Alternating bowel habits
#* Obstruction

''Screening:''

Alternative Methods (starting at age 50 yrs):

* Fecal Occult Blood Testing every 1 year
* Flexible sigmoidoscopy q5 yrs + FOBT q3 yrs
* Colonoscopy q10 yrs:
** Findings:
*** No polyps --> Repeat in 10 years
*** 1-2 polyps, < 1 cm, tubular, and low-grade dysplasia --> Low risk; Repeat in 5-10 yrs
*** > 3 polyps, > 1 cm, villous, or high-grade dysplasia --> High risk; Repeat in 1-3 yrs
*** > 10 polyps, piece-meal sessile polyp --> Ultra-high risk; Repeat in 2-6 months

Methods not ready for prime time:

* Fecal immunochemical testing (FIT)
* CT colonography
* Barium enema (apple-core lesion)

''Treatment:''

* Resection
* Pan CT for staging
* FOLFOX/FOLFIRI chemoregimens
** VEGF-i's like bevacizumab

''Associated Conditions:''

* [[FAP]]
* [[HNPCC]]
* Turcot - gut and CNS tumors
* Gardner's syndrome - colon cancer and jaw tumors
* Peutz–Jeghers syndrome - GI hamartomatous polyps and hyperpigmented macules on lips and oral mucosa






Glasgow Score (<8):

* Eye response (4 points)
* Verbal Response (5 points)
* Motor response (6 points)

Dog-eyes

Cranial nerve reflexes:

* Corneal reflex
* Pupillary light
* Gag 
* Cough

Apnea test






!! Framework:

# Be sure all the necessary people are present, turn off beepers, take as much time as necessary, sit closest to the primary people involved in the child's care (usually the parents), and have tissues available
# Determine what the child and family know
# Determine how much the child and family want to know
# Share the information
# Respond to the family's questions and feelings, giving them time and allowing for long silences
# Conclude with a plan for follow-up.

---

Buckman R. Breaking Bad News: A Guide for Healthcare Professionals. Baltimore, Md: Johns Hopkins University Press; 1992:15






Aka CAP

''Definition:'' If there was no healthcare admission in last 90 days or admission was within last 48 hours 

''Etiologies:''

* //Strep pneumo// -- Most common
* //M. catarrhalis//
* //H. flu// in smoker with COPD
* //Klebsiella// in alcoholic with aspiration
* //S. aureus// after infection with [[Flu]]
* //Legionella// if immunocompromised

''Treatment:'' IV 3rd-generation cephalosporin and macrolide or fluroquinolone like moxifloxacin






Or mild traumatic brain injury (mTBI)

Defined as head trauma without a brain bleed on imaging

Treatment is driven by classification:

* Mild --> patient may return home with monitoring
** No focal neurological deficits (FNDs)
** Any loss of consciousness (LOC) is < 60 seconds
** No headache or it is consistently improving
** No amnesia
* Severe --> Admit for neuro checks with potential follow-up imaging
** FNDs present
** LOC > 60 seconds
** Headache present
** Amnesia present

Regardless of initial classification, return to activities should be in a gradual step-wise fashion







''Presentation:''

White, cloudy lesions in the front chamber of the eye

* If present at birth --> likely due to [[TORCH Infections]]
* If present soon after birth --> likely due to a [[Metabolic Disease]] such as [[Galactosemia]]

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Surgery







''Presentation:''

* Premature delivery
* Low birth weight
* [[Jaundice|Neonatal Jaundice]]
* Purpuric rash
* ''Micro''cephaly
* Chorioretinitis
* Hearing loss
* Seizures
* ''Periventricular'' calcifications






<<list-links "[tag[Congenital Defects]]">>






<<list-links "[tag[Congenital Infections]]">>






''Presentation:''

* Intrauterine growth restriction
* [[Jaundice|Neonatal Jaundice]]
* Purpuric rash
* ''Hydrocephalus''
* Chorioretinitis
* Sensorineural hearing loss
* Seizures
* ''Diffuse'' intracranial calcifications






''Broken down by type:''

* Chemical:
** Caused by silver nitrate (when it was still used)
** Appears in first 24 hours
** Bilateral and non-purulent
** Use topical erythromycin instead to prevent
* Gonorrheal:
** Appears in first 2-7 days
** Bilateral and purulent
** Diagnose with culture on chocolate agar and PCR
** Treat with oral ceftriaxone
* Chlamydia:
** Appears in first 5-14 days
** Unilateral --> bilateral and mucoid --> purulent
** Diagnose with regular culture and PCR
** Treat with oral erythromycin
* Can also be caused by HSV (treat with acylovir) and other bacteria or viruses






''Categories:''

<<list-links "[tag[Connective Tissue Infections]]">>

''Consider these organisms in the following situations:''

* //Staphylococcus// is most common cause of these infections
* //Salmonella// is associated with [[Sickle Cell Disease]]
* //Pseudomonas// in penetrating wound or in area of soggy sneaker
* //Pseudomonas// or polymicrobial for diabetic foot ulcer
* //Vibro vulnificus// from uncooked oysters, especially in cirrhotic patient
