Assuming that you are actually engaging the patient with your data tracker, to do list, and regular visits, it is ok to treat the progress note as primarily for billing. ''Just get it done!''

''Rules:''

* Autopopulate and/or carry forward with copy/paste as much as possible. Consider editing in a separate document if your EMR doesn't provide you with a sidebar.
* Do update what needs updating:
** "HPI"
** Physical Exam
** Assessment/Plan
* Use past tense to stay consistent when feeding text forward
* Emphasis must be on "HPI" and the assessment because that's where others tend to skim to.
* Links problems to meds and interventions

''CC:'' ~~Patient Quote~~, Principal Diagnosis

''"HPI:"'' 

* [Date of Admission]: Admission HPI plus summarized update.
* [Hospital Day]: Over the past 24 hours, what you did, how it affected patient, and updates from other caregivers

''ROS:'' Carry forward

''Vitals:'' Autopopulate

''Physical Exam:'' Carry forward, but make sure to update changes!

''Labs:'' Autopopulate

''Imaging and Cultures:'' Carry forward

''Assessment:'' 

* Carry forward the one-liner but update the velocity of patient
* Explain the day's interventions

''Plan:'' By problem

* ~~Summary, Explanation, Labs, or Vitals~~
* Use abbreviations
* Be succinct
* Update verbs or eschew entirely






''Purpose:''

* Make it fast and interesting!
* Your opportunity for feedback and evaluation on your grasp of the hospital course and decision-making.
* Updating the team on latest events.
* Learning.

The point is not to inform the //attending//, they probably already know what's going on and could do your job more efficiently.

''Format (iSOAP):''

* Intro = one-liner reminder for team (very short)
* Subjective = story (don't use your papers)
** Run-down of all events since last rounds:
*** Each team decision/action --> patient's response
*** Includes night float, ancillary staff, consultant, and procedure events.
*** Should not include "no acute events overnight", HPI (just last 24 hours), ROS, or PMHx
* Objective = Only data from //today// that is needed for decision-making:
*# Vitals -- Tmax, HR range, BP range, RR range, Saturation #% on L/min
*# Relevant Physical -- //Not// head-to-toe
*# Relevant Labs -- Use conventions and changes from previous
*# Imaging -- Just interpretation
*# Cultures -- Every day until ruled out
* Assessment = Short one-liner to sum up:
** [Age] [Gender] [Dx] [Trajectory]
** Do not include PMHx, ROS, or HPI
** Try to use CMS language
* Plan by Problem (without reasoning unless prompted):
*# Principal Diagnosis
*# Active/changing issues most relevant to current hospital course
*# Chronic Issues
*# Quality assurance issues and dispo







That's me!






A form of aura to seizures where the person feels as if they are reliving an experience.

Most commonly originates from posterior temporal lobe.






''Set Up:''

* Use a quiet room without distractions
* Ask if the parents are comfortable having the child in the room
* Sit down with the parents
* Keep interruptions to a minimum
* Allow parents to ask questions
* Give advance notice that you have difficult news, so they have the opportunity to bring along someone with support.

''Assess:''

* Ask parents for their perception of the condition in question

''Warning:''

* Let the parents know you have difficult news.
* Use appropriate vocabulary
* Get to the point succinctly so there is time for clarification and questions

''Empathy:''

Address parental emotions with empathy:

* Expect emotion from parents and respond when appropriate
* Anticipate possible reactions of silence, disbelief, tears, denial, or anger
* Four parts:
** Observe the response
** Identify the emotion to yourself
** Identify the reason for the emotion. Ask the parent!
** Acknowledge and the validate the emotional reaction, being as warm and thoughtful as possible.

''Honesty:''

Be prepared to discuss your honest opinion:

* Do not offer uncertain prognosis
* Encourage hope for improvement with appropriate intervention
* Acknowledge the difficult aspect of having an unknown prognosis

''Assess:''

For understanding:

* Ask parents how they will explain this to family members

''Next Steps:''

* End the session with a clear plan for referrals and follow-up
* Write down the plan for parents so they can refer to it later.







Cognitive impairment with memory loss that is chronic and insidious with permanent effect (if a primary disorder).

''Spectrum:''

* Normal aging:
** Testing is negative
** No functional impairment
* Mild cognitive impairment:
** Testing is positive
** No functional impairment
* Dementia:
** Testing is positive
** Functional impairment

''Work-Up, aka "So you have a patient with dementia:"''

Is it reversible? --> Test BMP, LFT's, TSH/T4, B12, RPR, depression, CT/MRI:

* Testing is positive --> Secondary to reversible cause; Treat it
* Testing is negative --> Primary dementia etiology, diagnose it:
** [[Alzheimer's disease]]
** [[Frontotemporal dementia]]
** [[Lewy body dementia]]
** [[Vascular dementia]]
** [[Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease]]
** [[Normal pressure hydrocephalus]]

<<list-links "[tag[Documentation]]">>






Assuming that you have constructed your data tracker and to-do list and that you are [[presenting oral presentations properly|Spoken vs. Written H&P]], the main ''purpose'' of the written H&P is to ensure you ''have all the elements'' needed ''to bill'' at the proper level:

''PCP:'' [First] [Last]

''Other MD's:'' [First] [Last] [Specialty]

''Chief Complaint (CC):'' In ''your'' words as the provider so as to communicate the crux of the case

''History of Present Illness (HPI):''

* 1st Paragraph -- Timing and Characterization ([[SIQORAAA]])
** First line should not include pmhx unless severe or a dealbreaker for certain management scenarios
* 2nd Paragraph -- Review of systems (ROS) and history relevant to differential diagnosis (ddx)
** 2-3 lines per component with 2-3 components total
 * 3rd Paragraph -- Interventions thus far with response

''Complete ROS:'' "All 13 review of systems are negative except as listed in the HPI"

* Alternatively can utilize smartphrases or checkboxes

''Past Medical History (PMHx):'' List and enumerate 

* Include complications and baseline status if relevant

''Past Surgical History (PSHx):''

* Include scopes, caths, and other procedures as well

''Allergies:'' NKDA or [Drug Class] [Rxn]

''Medications:'' [Name] [Dose] [Frequency] [Route]

''Family History (FHx):'' Need explicit dz in specific family member or one statement saying "No history of [dz] in family"

''Social History (SHx):''

* Tobacco -- [ppd] x [yrs] = pack-years, quit date
* Alcohol -- drinks per day or drinks per week
* Drugs
* Living situation -- [Location] [Environment] [Help provided]
* ADL's -- Either independent in all ADL's or limitations
* Screening:
** Colon cancer
** Lung cancer
** Paps
** Mammograms
* Vaccines:
** Flu
** Tdap
** Pneumovax
** Zostervax

''Vitals:'' Just autopopulate with first time point

''Physical:'' Just autopopulate and edit as appropriate (helpful to abbreviate BS and write-out relevant stuff)

* Need 8 systems with 2-3 comma-separated elements apiece:
*# General appearance
*# HEENT
*# Neck
*# CV
*# Pulm
*# GI
*# MSK
*# Psych
*# Neuro
*# +/- GU

''Labs and Imaging:'' Autopopulate with as a much stuff as possible

''Assessment:'' Why diagnosis is correct and why others are wrong

* Helpful to use phrases like "complicated" and "severe"

''Plan''






* ropinarole
* pramipexole
* bromocriptine

''Pathophysiology:''

Fevers lower the seizure threshold and children are more susceptible because of their developing brains

''Presentation:''

Criteria for categorization use simple and complex in a different way then used to describe seizures in general.

A febrile seizure is ''simple'' if it fulfills ''all three criteria'':

* Only one over 24 hours
* Lasts less than 15 minutes
* Generalized

''Diagnosis:''

If simple*, no diagnostic studies needed

If complex*, consider EEG, LP, and/or MRI depending on suspected etiology

''Treatment:''

Always use benzos to abort

If simple*, tylenol good for symptomatic relief from fever

If complex* and suspected to be epilepsy (recurrent), [[AEDs]] are valid to start






''Breast Milk Instructions:''

After pumping, breast milk can sit in the fridge for 3-6 days. It can sit in freezer storage for 3-6 months. Don't thaw with microwave. Once thawed, do not refreeze.

Boppy nursing pillows are great for comfort and support to breast feeding.

''Formula Instructions:''

Generally, use 1 scoop of formula for every 2 oz of water, but check instructions on any given product.

Tap water is fine for use in mixing. No need to boil it. Only buy "infant water" if you know that your tap water doesn't contain fluoride.

Feed formula and pumped breast milk in a bottle. You do not need a special bottle unless your baby is really fussy with gas. The nipples for bottles change by age range. Wean off a bottle at the latest by 2 years old.

''Special Needs:''

If baby is a premie, feed neosure, which has higher calories.

If baby has milk protein allergy, use alimentum or nutramigen formulas. If baby isn't tolerating these (they smell and taste bad), you can trial soy-based formulas, but watch out for effects from estrogen content.

''Transitions:''

Can start giving plain water at about 4-6 months when the kidneys are better able to maintain osmolarity. Using a sippy cup early on helps train for weaning. Babies and young children don't need any other beverages besides water and formula/milk. Any juice should be kept at a strict minimum.

Solid foods can be introduced around 4-6 months according to these cues:

* Showing interest in your foods
* Supported sitter
* Tongue thrust reflex is going away

Solid foods are good around this time in order to stimulate oral-motor development and bolster falling iron stores. Only introduce one solid food per 5-7 days. Watch for signs of rash, vomiting, and diarrhea with each new food. Let baby feed at a quantity according to interest. Grain cereal is a good starting point. Put it in a bowl with spoon.

Baby food are classified by stages:

# Liquidy puree and only one ingredient. Give when baby is a supported sitter.
# Thicker with multiple ingredients. Give when baby is an independent sitter.
# Even thicker with chunks and ingredients contain protein. Give when baby is a crawler.

Table foods can be introduced at 8 months, but watch out for choking! Puffs are good for peace of mind because they dissolve.

''Support:''

Low income families can get formula feeds through WIC, which provides enfamil powder.

''Anticipatory Guidance:''

Babies naturally start pooping less at 2-3 weeks because their GI tracts are maturing and absorbing more nutrients and water.






''Algorithm aka "So you have a fever and cough":''

Consider [[Flu]] if patient also has myalgias.

Pediatric patients have viral etiologies more commonly than adults.

Blood culture should be done and sputum can be done, but ''chest x-ray (CXR)'' and SpO2 are most important for diagnosis:

* If CXR is negative --> [[Bronchitis]]; PO macrolide (azithromycin), doxycycline, or fluoroquinolone (FQ, moxifloxacin); Patient goes home
* If CXR has consolidation --> [[Pneumonia]]; Is the patient immunosuppressed?:
** Patient is immunosuppressed --> Consider [[PCP]], //Legionella//, or fungal pneumonia
** Patient is not immunosuppressed --> How recently was patient admitted to a healthcare facility?:
*** Patient was not admitted within past 90 days or was currently admitted within last 48 hours --> [[Community-Acquired Pneumonia]] (CAP); Treat with IV 3rd-generation cephalosporin and macrolide or FQ (moxi).
*** Patient was admitted within past 90 days or currently admitted greater than 48 hours ago --> [[Healthcare-Associated Pneumonia]] (HCAP); Treat with IV Pipericillin-Tazobactam and Vancomycin.
* If CXR has cavitation --> Patient has cavitary lesion; Get CT Scan:
** Fungal abscess
** [[Tuberculosis]]
** Bacterial Abscess; Treat with 3rd-generation cephalosporin and clindamycin

''Prophylaxis:'' Give to everyone except infants, elderly, and pregnant women every year. Healthcare personnel should get before the winter months start.

<<list-links "[tag[Gastroenterology]]">>






Stomach churns and digests food with acids

Duodenum absorbs:

* Carbohydrates
** Malabsorption --> bloating, flatulence, and weight loss
* Folate
** Malabsorption --> [[Macrocytic Anemia]]
* Iron
** Malabsorption --> [[Microcytic Anemia]]
* Calcium
** Malabsorption --> [[Osteoporosis]]
 
Liver/gallbladder secrete bile to help dissolve fat

Pancreas secretes enzymes to digest protein

Terminal ileum absorbs:

* B12
** Malabsorption --> [[Macrocytic Anemia]] and neurological signs
* Vitamin A
** Malabsorption --> Night blindness
* Vitamin D
** Malabsorption --> Osteoporosis
* Vitamin E
** Malabsorption --> Nystagmus
* VItamin K
** Malabsorption --> Bleeding






''Pathophysiology:''

Delayed emptying of the stomach due to [[DM]] or idiopathic

''Presentation:''

* Chronic nausea/vomiting
* Abdominal pain with eating
* Peripheral neuropathy

''Diagnosis:''

* EGD to rule out other diseases
* Gastric emptying study:
** Positive if:
*** >60% of contents remain after 2 hours
*** >10% of contents remain after 4 hours
** Requires patient to be off opioids and anticholinergics as well as to maintain blood glucose control

''Treatment:''

* Avoid opioids and anticholinergics
* Maintain consistent glucose control
* Pro-kinetic agents:
** PO Metoclopramide for chronic maintenance
** IV erythromycin for flares
** Domperidone only for compassionate use
* Have low-fiber, small-volume meals 






Or violence against women and girls (VAWG); or sexual assault

''Prevention:''

Successful programs are almost always multi-faceted.

Large effects can be achieved in a small amount of time.

Effective preventive interventions: 

* In Kenya, [["No Means No"|http://www.whatworks.co.za/about/global-programme/global-programme-projects/innovation-projects/item/37-women-and-girls-empowerment-and-boys-transformation-program-to-prevent-vawg]], Changing gender norms in middle-schoolers
** Girls:
*** Empowerment
*** Situational awareness
*** Verbal skills (one of most effective components by self-report)
*** Physical self-defense
** Boys:
*** Healthy gender norms
*** Positive masculinity
*** Limited bystander intervention
* In Canada and Stanford, [["EAAA"|https://sara.stanford.edu/prevention-education-outreach/enhanced-assess-acknowledge-act-eaaa-program]]
* Bystander intervention
* Modifying men's social norms, "RealConsent"
* Empowerment programs, "IMPower"

Outcomes of interest:

* Rape
* Unplanned pregnancy
* STI's
* Test scores

Important Characteristics:

* Community buy-in
* Transparency
* Local implementers
* Scalability






''Pathophysiology:''

Incompetent lower esophageal sphincter allows regurgitation of stomach acid into the esophagus --> esophagitis.

Chronic exposure to acid --> metaplasia (Barrett's Esophagus) --> 30-50x increased risk of dysplastic change --> adenocarcinoma.

''Presentation:''

* Dysphagia/odynophagia
* Typical symptoms:
** Burning chest pain:
*** Worse with recumbency and spicy foods
*** Better with sitting up and antacids
* Atypical symptoms:
** Hoarseness
** Coughing
** Stridor
** "Nocturnal asthma"
** Halitosis

''Management algorithm:''

Signs and symptoms of GERD:

* Are there alarm symptoms (nausea/vomiting, anemia, weight loss)?
** No alarm symptoms --> Treat with PPI plus lifestyle changes for 6 weeks; Do they improve?
*** Patient improves --> Scale back PPI as tolerated
*** Patient does not improve --> Perform EGD with biopsy
** Alarm symptoms are present --> Perform EGD with biopsy:
*** Findings are GERD --> Continue treatment with PPI
*** Findings are metaplasia --> Raise to high-dose PPI; Perform serial EGD surveillance
*** Findings are dysplasia --> Local ablation + PPI; Perform serial EGD surveillance
*** Findings are adenocarcinoma --> Staging, resection, chemo, radiation

''Other diagnostics:''

* 24-hour pH monitor useful for uncertain diagnosis
* Manometry useful prior to surgery

''Other treatment:''

* Nissen fundoplication acceptable if patient can't tolerate PPI or requests the surgery

The refugee experience is rife with ACEs. 

Important for all refugees to undergo screening: nutritional deficiencies, STIs, men's health, women's health, mental health, inactivity, disrupted education.






''Pathophysiology:''

Hematogenous seeding of joint with Neisseria gonorrheae

''Presentation:''

Red, hot, swollen, tender joint. +/- toxic appearance.

Patient has STD or risk factors:

* Cervicitis or urethritis
* Sex worker
* HIV or syphilis

''Diagnosis:''

Arthorcentesis shows greater than 50,000 WBC, gram-stain shows nothing, and NAAT is positive for Gonorrhea

''Treatment:''

Ceftriaxone IV 7-14 days

Doxycycline or azithromycin for empiric coverage of Chlamydia






''Pathophysiology:''

Caused by overproduction (such as in [[tumor lysis syndrome|Tumor Lysis Syndrome]] or under-elimination of uric acid --> Deposition of monosodium urate in the joint

Those with regular gout attacks usually suffer from combination of genetic predisposition, dietary risk factors, and kidney underexcretion (e.g. CKD or medications like hydrochlorothiazide).

Dietary risk factors include large amounts of red meat, alcohol, and/or fructose.

''Presentation:''

Red, hot, swollen, tender joint. Often times in form of podagra (big toe).

''Diagnosis:''

Arthrocentesis shows negatively-birefringent, needle-shaped crystals.

If there are //repeated// attacks, measure a serum uric acid level.

''Treatment:''

Treat the flare with NSAIDS, colchicine, and/or steroids.

Prevent recurrence with dietary lifestyle modification and medication change as indicated.

If chronic recurrence occurs despite lifestyle modification, treat with allopurinol. Do not initiate during flare, but continue if flare occurs during induction. Prophylax with low dose colchicine, NSAIDS, and steroids. Shoot for serum uric acid levels below 6.

If gout is thought to be caused by decreased elimination, consider probenecid as treatment.

Causes epiglottitis and meningitis

''Prophylaxis:''

Getting disease at less than 2 years old does not confer immunity. Hib vaccine only covers type B strain of bacteria. 






''Pathophysiology:''

Infectious organism that is prevalent in large proportion of population

''Presentation:''

* 85% of those infected are asymptomatic
* Those who are symptomatic have dyspepsia
* 15% have peptic ulcer disease
* ~1% have a [[MALToma]]

''Diagnosis:''

* Serology useful if:
** First time testing
** Never been treated
** Symptomatic
*** Then treat if positive, otherwise doesn't mean anything
* Urea breath test useful for initial diagnosis
* Stool antigen good to check for eradication
* EGD + biopsy is gold standard (follow-up with histology, not culture if needed)

''Treatment:''

* Triple therapy:
** PPI
** Amoxicillin (or metronidazole if allergic)
** Clarithromycin






''Uses:''

If you have a new patient with no history in the chart and you need to build from scratch

If you are new learner and you need to put together info from different sources

''Cost:''

Time -- first you put together the miner, then the tracker, then the actual note (initially maybe 1.5 hours total; 10 minutes for miner itself). Counteract by practicing "[[Beat the Duck]]"

Other tasks you need to get done such as admit orders, calls, and other patients

''Benefits:''

Gives you a sloppy run at putting together the information

Perfect practice makes perfect

Repetitive engagement with the patient

Guides what you ask the patient when you interview

''Goal:''

Eventually to eliminate the miner from your workflow once you're organized in how you put together your tracker

<<list-links "[tag[Head Trauma]]">>






The key task when diagnosing headache is identifying ''red flags'' that point to secondary causes requiring further workup:

* Fever
* Focal neurological deficits
* New onset after age 50
* True thunderclap onset
* Progressive nausea/vomiting

''Algorithm, aka "So you have a headache":''

Are there red flags?:

* If ''red flags present'' --> Secondary Headache; Perform some combination of head imaging, LP, or biopsy for ddx including:
** [[Brain Inflammation]]
** Tumor
** [[Intracranial hemorrhage|Head Trauma]]
** [[Idiopathic Intracranial Hypertension]]
* If no red flags --> Primary Headache; usually can diagnose clinically:
** [[Tension Headache]]
** [[Migraine]]
** [[Analgesic-Rebound Headache]]
** [[Cluster Headache]]






Or the confidential adolescent interview:

* Home situation and safety there
* Education and/or vocation
* Activities and friends
* Drug use
* Depression/mood sxs
* Suicidality
* Sexual activity

Shortcuts in thinking that can lead to error

''Modes of Thinking:''

''Analytical'' is deliberate, considering all the available data. It relies on deduction. Early on, this is how you should be thinking all the time.

''Intuitive'' is a reaction based on pattern recognition. It relies on experience. It is ok and expected to rely on intuition as you move further into your career, but you need to know when to switch back in toanalysis when you sense that something isn't quite right. ''Heuristics'' are means of intuitive thinking.

''Common Heuristics:''

''Representational'' -- you assign an illness script to a case even when the data supporting that script doesn't actually exist (novice mistake).

''Availability'' -- you increase the likelihood of a diagnosis because it is familiar to you or interesting in your head

''Recency'' -- you increase the likelihood of a diagnosis because you just saw it in another case or read about it

''Severity'' -- you increase the likelihood of a diagnosis because it is deadly or scary --> defensive medicine

''Anchoring'' -- pieces of an illness script are present, but you prematurely decide on a diagnosis and ignore contradicting data; can also happen when a specialist tells you the diagnosis and you believe them without questioning the pieces that don't fit






''Pathophys:''

Failure of inhibitory neurons from the Auerbach and Meissner Plexuses to migrate to the distal colon --> distal colon cannot relax smooth muscle contraction

Severity depends on how proximal the failure of migration is

''Presentation:''

* Palpable colon present
* About 90% present as [[failure to pass meconium|Failure to Pass Meconium]]; explosive diarrhea on digital rectal exam (1)
* About 10% present as chronic diarrhea with overflow incontinence (2)

''Diagnosis:''

* X-ray shows dilation (functional colon) and seemingly normal colon (non-functional colon)
* Diagnose (1) with contrast enema
* Diagnose (2) with anorectal manometry --> increased tone
* Best test = biopsy of colon --> no plexus

''Treatment:''

Surgically resect non-functional colon






Aka Human Immunodeficiency Virus

''Pathophysiology:''

Viral lifecycle for dummies:

* CD4 cells have CXCR4 and CCR5 transporters which HIV exploits to get past the cell membrane
* Once inside reverse transcriptase transcribes the viral RNA into DNA, which enters the nucleus
* The viral DNA is transcribed into many more copies of viral RNA, which is packaged into new particles by protease.

Means of transmission:

* Sex (0.2% chance)
* Intravenous drug use (0.3%)
* Vertical transmission (25%)

''Presentations:''

[[Acute Retroviral Syndrome]] or [[AIDS]]

''Treatment:''

Antiretroviral therapy:

* Usually in "2 + 1" configuration:
** 2 nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NRTI's) plus:
*** 1 non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor (NNRTI)
*** -or- 1 protease inhibitor
*** -or- 1 fusion inhibitor
*** -or- 1 entry inhibitor
* Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is emtricitabine and tenofovir (both NRTI's)
* Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) is emtricitabine, tenofovir, +/- raltegravir (integrase inhibitor)
* In pregnancy:
** Mom should be on 2 + 1 therapy
** In case of acute diagnosis, use AZT for prophylaxis








Aka Hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancer or Lynch syndrome

''Pathophysiology:''

Mutations in DNA mismatch repair

''Presentation:''

Suspect in families with:

* At least 3 cases of cancer (colorectal, endometrial, or ovarian)
* Spanning at least 2 generations
* With at least 1 case happening earlier than typical

Aka herpes simplex virus






Or commercial sexual exploitation (CSE)

Consent does not factor into official definitions, just acts of exploitation and coercion. Also does not require human movement.

''Screening:''

"Have you ever traded sex for money, drugs, or shelter?"

Red flags:

* Chronically truant, homeless, or runaway youth
* Excess cash
* Hotel room keys
* Multiple cell phones, texting apps, and/or social media profiles
* Signs of branding (tattoos or jewelry)
* Having expensive items with no known source of income
* Lying about age/false identification/inconsistencies in information being reported
* Dramatic personality change
* Evasive behavior, especially around "new boyfriend"; talk of being "taken care of"
* Disengagement from school, sports, community
* Lack of knowledge about community or whereabouts
* Provocative clothing, sex toys, multiple condoms, lube, or other sex devices

How to identify at-risk youth:

* Ask specific questions to screen for risk factors or CSE involvement
* Increase efforts to find chronic runaway or truant kids
* Learn about gang activity from local law enforcement
* Ask about STI/STDs, pregnancy, and unexplained injuries
* Observe communication patterns; who talks to whom, who doesn't talk, who is in control

''Engagement:''

Principles:

* Maintain a compassionate and non-judgmental attitude at all times
* Be consistent: follow through on everything and don't make promises you can't keep
* Trust and relationship building: this is a slow process, and relationship testing is to be expected
* Cultural competency: be sensitive to the unique cultural needs and experiences of each person. Be aware of your own beliefs, biases, and cultural worldview
* Safety: Focus on safe housing, harm reduction, and creating safety strategies for youth
* Self-determination and empowerment: youth should have information relevant to their situation and be encouraged to make informed decisions whenever possible.

What questions do I ask?

* What kind of support do you need?
* What happened to you?
* Sometimes people trade sex for money or because they have to survive, has that happened to you?
* I'm concerned about your safety, are there places that are dangerous for you to go? Are there people that are dangerous for you to be around right now?
* I'm concerned that you are in the life. I will not judge you or anything you tell me. I'm here to listen if you ever want to talk to want support getting out.

''Resources:''

* [[Stolen Youth|https://stolenyouth.org/]]
* [[Physicians Against the Trafficking of Humans|http://www.doc-path.org/]]
* [[Futures without Violence|https://www.futureswithoutviolence.org/is-your-relationship-affecting-your-health-safety-card/]]
* [[Be Free Textline|https://polarisproject.org/befree-textline]]

Aka hemolytic uremic syndrome

* Supportive --> plasma exchange

''Pathophys:''

Low blood glucose associated with LGA, SGA, diabetic mothers, and IUGR.

''Presentation:''

Spectrum of asymptomatic, jitters, tremor --> seizure, and lethargy.

''Diagnosis:''

Check blood sugar and appropriate tests for infection

''Treatment:''

* If asymptomatic --> feed
* If symptomatic --> IV bolus of D50 (2 mg/kg)
* If persistent after bolus --> IV drip of D5 or D10

By time course:

* Acute:
** Infection
** Infarction
** Iatrogenic
* Chronic:
** Autoimmune
** Deposition Disease
** Tumor

By etiology:

*Pituitary causes:
** Primary or metastatic mass
** Infiltration (hemachromatosis, lymphocytic hypophysitis)
** Hemorrhage (pituitary apoplexy) or infarction (Sheehan syndrome)
** [[Empty Sella Syndrome]]
* Hypothalamic causes:
** Mass lesions
** Radiation therapy
** Infiltration (sarcoidosis)
** Trauma to skull base
** Infections (tuberculous meningitis)

''Presentation:''

By time course:

* Acute:
** Hypotension and tachycardia (from cortisol deficiency)
** Lethargy and coma (from thyroid deficiency)
* Chronic:
** Hormones tend to drop off in step-wise fashion: 1) FSH/LH 2) GH 3) TSH 4) ACTH
** [[Amenorrhea|Primary Amenorrhea]], decreased libido, fatigability

By etiology:

* ACTH deficiency (secondary adrenal insufficiency):
** Postural hypotension, tachycardia, fatigue, weight loss, hypoglycemia, eosinophilia
** Mild hyponatremia due to preserved ADH release
** Normal K+ (RAAS preserved)
** No hyperpigmentation changes (as opposed to primary adrenal insufficiency with increased ACTH)
* Hypothyroidism (central):
** Fatigue, cold intolerance, constipation, dry skin, bradycardia, slowed deep tendon reflexes
* Gonadotropins:
** Women: Amenorrhea
** Men: Infertility, loss of libido

''Diagnosis:''

Acute --> T4 and cortisol levels

Chronic --> [[Insulin stim test|Insulin Stimulation Test]], vasopressin stim test, MRI

''Treatment:''

Hormone replacement

''Follow-up:''

If recently pregnant --> [[Sheehan's Syndrome]] workup

If tumor present --> evaluate for pituitary apoplexy

''First'' what it is ''not'':

Looking at the labs and imaging, drawing a conclusion with the diagnosis, then going back to the history and physical to fit that diagnosis.

The ''real goal'':

It is expected to be convoluted and comprehensive as you speak with the patient. The goal though is to organize that information around a differential diagnosis and to select only the relevant pieces as you present.

''Outline:''

* "1st Paragraph" -- Timing and characterization:
** [[SIQORAAA]] 
* Generate differential diagnosis (3-5 max):
** From here on, every paragraph is influenced by differential and then feeds back into it
* "2nd Paragraph" -- Review of Systems relevant to the ddx:
** Next you would record [[PAMHRFOSS]], ''but'' any of this relevant to ddx would be included in paragraph 2, the rest goes unreported in presentation
* Physical Exam:
** 1st Tier is screening exam you perform on every patient. No need to present unless relevant.
** 2nd Tier is relevant maneuvers to ddx
* Labs and Imaging:
** 1st Tier is baseline findings for admission or clinic
** 2nd Tier is diagnostic tests relevant to final items still likely on ddx
* All of this feeds into your final diagnosis, which guides treatment
** Tomorrow, follow outline again from the lens of this is how we managed, did it work, how does that influence how we proceed?

''Work-up:''

Upright abdominal radiograph:

* X-ray shows free air under diaphragm --> Perforation; Perform exploratory laparotomy and give IV antibiotics
* X-ray shows dilated loops of small bowel and multiple air-fluid levels --> [[Small Bowel Obstruction]]; Perform ex lap
* X-ray is "normal" --> Perform abdominal CT:
** CT shows mild [[Diverticulitis]]; Put on liquid diet and oral antibiotics
** CT shows severe diverticulitis; Make NPO and on IV abx
** CT shows diverticular abscess; Make NPO, give IV abx, and perform incision and drainage






''Spectrum:''

* Coma:
** Depressed cerebral function (assess with EEG)
** Brain stem works (Assess with [[reflexes|Brain stem reflexes]])
** Heart works (assess with EKG)
** Motor/sensory work (assess with physical exam)
* Persistent vegetative state:
** No cerebral function
** Brain stem works
** Heart works
** Motor/sensory work
* Brain death:
** No cerebral function
** No brain stem function
** Heart works
** No motor/sensory function
* Locked-in syndrome:
** Cerebrum works
** Most of brain stem works
** Heart works
** No motor function
** Sensation works






''Look for red flags:''

* Bowel/bladder incontinence
* Saddle anesthesia
* Focal neurological deficits
* Rapidly progressing

''Algorithm, aka "So you have lower back pain:"''

Are there red flags?:

* Red flags are present --> Cord Compression; Give dexamethasone; Perform X-ray and MRI --> Interventions:
** Drain hematoma
** I&D + Abx for abscess
** Radiation for tumor
** Surgery for fracture
** Etc
* No red flags, but signs specific for:
** [[Disc Herniation]]
** [[Spinal Osteophyte]]
** [[Spinal Stenosis]]
** [[Spinal Compression Fracture]]
* No red flags and non-specific symptoms --> Likely [[Musculoskeletal Back Pain]]; Recommend NSAIDS and exercises --> Reassess in 6 weeks

** If D-Xylose absorbed --> Enzyme deficiency; Give pancreatic enzyme supplementation
** If D-Xylose not absorbed --> Intestinal luminal border pathology; Perform EGD with biopsy

Two days ago, I participated in the March for Our Lives in NYC. I tend to feel reluctant about attending protests because I feel that they orient you in opposition against an adversary. Sometimes it is necessary to pick a side and fight for a cause, but in general, I feel that progress comes when we work together to find common ground. Protest philosophy aside, here is what I believe, I encourage you to respectfully agree or disagree with me in the comments:

# Too many children in the United States die from gun violence. Not just by the acts of of mass shooters, but by their own family and fellow community members as well.
# Effective prevention will require multiple strategies. Of course we should screen and treat those with mental health conditions, there is plenty of room to improve in this domain, but not every person who commits an act of violence has a diagnosable condition. In general, we need to invest in the well-being of our people. A person with a sense of safety, purpose, and happiness is less likely to commit acts of violence. And...
# Thoughtful regulation of weapons commerce and possession has a part to play. No, regulation won't completely solve the problem, just as seat belts don't completely eliminate motor vehicle accident deaths. Yes, it will come at the sacrifice of certain civil liberties. But there is some compromise to be found that helps save lives. Children are one of our nation's greatest assets. I prioritize their lives over the right to own an AR-15 or the right to forgo background checks.
# This is a process, and I am not an expert. Other large, diverse countries have made significant impacts in reducing gun violence. We should have the humility to consult them on what has worked and what has not. Also, as with most policy, it is important to support a robust research community in order to measure and assess the quality of our interventions.
# Together we can do this. Who among us wants to see our children die? We will have disagreements over how best to accomplish our goals, but none of us has all the answers. To succumb to petty fighting, is to allow the status quo of death to continue. We need to listen and compromise. Together we can do this.

''Physiology:''

In order to menstruate, you need intact [[HPA Axis]] and intact female reproductive organs.

HPA Axis:

*Hypothalamus releases GnRH (example problem etiology is [[Kallman Syndrome]])
** GnRH stimulates anterior pituitary gland to release FSH and LH (example problem etiology is [[Craniopharyngioma]])
*** FSH and LH inhibit activity of the hypothalamus
*** FSH and LH stimulate ovaries to release estrogen and progesterone (E&P)(example problem etiology is [[Turner Syndrome]])
**** E&P stimulate the uterine endothelium to build up a lining then shed it as a bleed
**** E&P inhibit activity of the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary

Female Reproductive Organs and Phenotype:

* X,X genotype:
** Codes for vulva, vagina, and clitoris
** Codes for Mullerian ducts which develop into the upper third of the vagina, the cervix, the uterus, and Fallopian tubes
** Codes for ovaries which release E&P which stimulate secondary female sexual characteristics
* X,Y genotype:
** Codes for testes:
*** Testes produce Mullerian Inhibitory Factor which inhibits development of Mullerian ducts leading to development of Wolffian ducts into male reproductive tract instead
*** Testes produce testosterone, which transform outer vulva, vagina, and clitoris into penis and scrotum. Testosterone also stimulates development of secondary male sexual characteristics.

** If positively-birefringent, rhomboid-shaped crystals --> ''Pseudogout'' (calcium pyrophosphate), treat flare with colchicine, NSAIDS, and/or steroids
** If negatively-birefringent, needle-shaped crystals --> [[Gout]]
* If greater than 50,000 WBC, organisms present, and no crystals --> ''Septic Joint'', Do gram stain:
** If gram-positive organisms in clusters --> [[Staphylococcal Septic Joint]]
** If nothing shows up on gram stain --> [[Gonorrheal Septic Joint]]

[[Hyperbilirubinemia]] of the newborn

Danger is that blood brain barrier (BBB) is not mature in the neonate --> conjugated bilirubin can cross and cause [[neurotoxicity|Bilirubin-Induced Neurologic Dysfunction]].

Every newborn should be screened (usually by transcutaneous route) ~48 hours after discharge. Determine significance of [[bilirubin |Bilirubin]] level with [[BiliTool|http://bilitool.org/]].

''Conceptualization by anatomy:''

*''Pre''-hepatic pathology is associated with unconjugated bilirubinemia. Typically an issue of hemolysis or hemorrhage.
* ''Intra''hepatic pathology is associated with mixed bilirubinemia. Think of metabolic diseases like:
** [[Crigler-Najjar Syndrome]] and [[Gilbert's Syndrome]] (more of a pre-hepatic picture)
** [[Dubin-Johnson Syndrome]] and [[Rotor Syndrome]] (more of a post-hepatic picture)
* ''Post''-hepatic pathology is associated with conjugated bilirubinemia. Think of issues like:
** [[Biliary Atresia]] aka obstruction (almost never gallstones or cancer like you would expect with adults)
** [[Sepsis]]
** Metabolic disease

''Risk Factors:''

* Measured bilirubin is determined to be high risk based on nomogram or BiliTool
* Jaundice appears within the first 24 hours
* Identified ABO incompatibility
* Gestational age 35-36 weeks
* Prior sibling needed phototherapy
* Physical exam reveals cephalohematoma or bruising
* Exclusively breastfeeding with poor intake or weight loss
* East Asian race

''Determining whether jaundice is pathologic:''

*Physiologic jaundice:
** Newborns have shorter RBC lifespan --> greater turnover of hemoglobin
**Shows up after 72 hours old
**Lasts less than a week (2 weeks if preemie; there is a steep rise in [[UDP-GT]] at the time of birth --> lower conjugation capacity if born prematurely)
**Predominately unconjugated
**Bili levels rise less than 5 per day
*Pathologic jaundice:
**Shows up less than 24 hours old
**Lasts greater than a week (>= 2 weeks if preemie)
**Bili levels rise >= 5 per day

''Work-up aka "So you have a yellow baby":''

Initial blood test to consider is ''bilirubin'' (also get Coomb's, CBC, and retic count):

*Bilirubin predominately ''conjugated'':
** Work-up for ''obstruction'' with hepatic ultrasound and/or HIDA scan.
**Also consider sepsis and metabolic disease in your differential
*Bilirubin predominately ''unconjugated'' --> Get ''Coomb's test'':
**Coomb's test is ''positive ''--> Problem is ''isoimmunization'' from Mom
**Coomb's test is ''negative ''--> Measure ''hemoglobin'' (hgb):
***Hgb is ''low ''--> Problem is ''hemorrhage ''such as cephalohematoma
***Hgb is ''high ''--> Problem is ''transfusion ''such as from twin-twin, delayed clamping, or maternal
***Hgb is ''normal ''--> Measure ''reticulocyte count'':
****Retic is ''normal ''--> Problem is concerning ''reabsorption ''of bilirubin such as from the "[[Breast Jaundices]]"
****Retic is ''high ''--> Problem is from ''hemolysis ''such as with [[G6PD Deficiency]], Pyruvate Kinase Deficiency, or [[Sickle Cell Disease]]

''Treatment:''

Promote healthy breast feeding!

Overall goal is to turn unconjugated bilirubin into conjugated bilirubin so it can be excreted. Usually accomplished with blue light phototherapy. Maintaining adequate hydration is also important.

If bilirubin level is very high, you may need to use exchange transfusion or IVIG. 

Threshold for treatment is adjusted by presence of risk factors for neurotoxicity such as isoimmune hemolytic disease, G6PD deficiency, asphyxia, significant lethargy, temperature instability, sepsis, or acidosis.






''Preparation:''

Make sure you have materials like towels, warmer, thermometer, pulse oximeter, suction, respiratory equipment.

Familiarize yourself with the basics of the case such as gravida and para status, gestational age, as well as amount of prenatal care that the mother got.

''After time zero (delivery):''

First task is to stimulate baby to prevent primary apnea. Methods include rubbing baby with towels or flicking the feet.

SpO2 target is 60-65%. First step to clear airway is to suction mouth and then nose. If not meeting target, consider positive pressure ventilation (PPV) followed by intubation.

Heart rate (HR) target is greater than 100. If not, consider PPV.

''After minute one:''

Measure first [[APGAR |APGAR]] score. Target is 7-10. Less than 7 requires some sort of targeted intervention.

SpO2 target is 80-85%. If not meeting target, consider positive pressure ventilation (PPV) with increased FiO2 followed by intubation.

Heart rate (HR) target is greater than 100. If 60 < HR < 100, consider PPV. If HR < 60, need CPR with 3:1 compression to ventilation ratio. 

''After minute five:''

Measure second APGAR score with same targets.

SpO2 target is 90-95%. If not meeting target, consider positive pressure ventilation (PPV) with increased FiO2 followed by intubation.

Heart rate (HR) target is greater than 100. If 60 < HR < 100, consider PPV. If HR < 60, need CPR with 3:1 compression to ventilation ratio. 

''After minute ten:''

Continue measuring APGAR scores until greater than 7. Then proceed to [[well-baby exam|Well-Baby Exam]].

''Potential problems encountered:''

* [[Transient tachypnea of the newborn|Transient Tachypnea of the Newborn]]
* [[Respiratory distress syndrome|Respiratory Distress Syndrome]]
* [[Hypoglycemia]]






''Pathophys:''

Caused by genetic factors and/or folate deficiency --> caudal spine fails to fully form

''Presentation:''

* Prenatal care:
** Quad screen shows elevated AFP
** Ultrasound shows hole in spine
* No prenatal care:
** At birth, physical exam reveals anywhere on spectrum from tuft of hair to full meningomyelocele

''Diagnosis:''

Tuft of hair with slight dimple is occulta

Bulge with just spinal fluid is meningocele

Bulge with spinal fluid and cord is meningomyelocele

''Treatment:''

Surgical correction

''Follow-up:''

For [[Arnold-Chiari malformation|Chiari malformation]], hydrocephalus, and focal neurological deficits below the lesion

''Risk Factors:''

* Food access and means to purchase
* Degree of physical activity
* Degree of education for parents
* Medication use (antidepressants, antipsychotics, antibiotics)
* Sleep hygiene
* Cultural portion distortion

''Presentation:''

* Elevated BMI
* Acanthosis nigricans
* Elevated blood pressure

''Treatment Guidelines:''

Principles to success:

* Best to target as early as possible--it's a myth that kids will outgrow
* 5-10% weight loss is a good initial goal
* Family involvement is key
* Motivational interviewing is excellent for communication
* Goals should be [[SMART]] and iterative

Staged approach:

# All patients starting at age 2 with PCP:
#* 5 fruits/vegetables per day
#* 2 hours or less of discretionary screen-time per day
#** Target first meals in front of screen, which reduce mindful eating
#* 1 hour of rigorous physical activity
#* 0 sugar-sweetened beverages
# PCP and dietician:
#* Meal plan implemented
# Comprehensive interdisciplinary-intervention with obesity, nutritionist, exercise therapist, behaviorist
#* 25 flexible contact hours over 6-12 hours
#* Stimulus control key
# Tertiary intervention
#* Residential treatment
#* Orlistat rx
#* Bariatric surgery
#* Low-calorie tube-feeding

Tips and tricks:

* My fitness pal app for counting calories
* Park far away or walk from next closest transit stop
* Reduce number of times eating out of home






Aka obsessive compulsive disorder

''Definition as per DSM-5:''

A.    Presence of obsessions, compulsions, or both:

Obsessions are defined by (1) and (2):

1. Recurrent and persistent thoughts, urges, or impulses that are experienced, at some time during the disturbance, as intrusive and unwanted, and that in most individuals cause marked anxiety or distress.

2.The individual attempts to ignore or suppress such thoughts, urges, or images, or to neutralize them with some other thought or action (i.e., by performing a compulsion).

Compulsions are defined by (1) and (2):

1. Repetitive behaviors (e.g., hand washing, ordering, checking) or mental acts (e.g., praying, counting, repeating words silently) that the individual feels driven to perform in response to an obsession or according to rules that must be applied rigidly.

2.The behaviors or mental acts are aimed at preventing or reducing anxiety or distress, or preventing some dreaded event or situation; however, these behaviors or mental acts are not connected in a realistic way with what they are designed to neutralize or prevent, or are clearly excessive.

Note: Young children may not be able to articulate the aims of these behaviors or mental acts.

B. The obsessions or compulsions are time-consuming (e.g., take more than 1 hour per day) or cause clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other important areas of functioning.

C. The obsessive-compulsive symptoms are not attributable to the physiological effects of a substance (e.g., a drug of abuse, a medication) or another medical condition.

D. The disturbance is not better explained by the symptoms of another mental disorder.







<<list-links "[tag[On the Wards]]">>






''Ways to engage:''

As a physician:

* Screen: In the past year, have you ever used drugs that were not prescribed to you?
* Refer to appropriate providers.
* Learn how to use naloxone and educate patients on its use.
* Get waiver to prescribe buprenorphine.

Strategies for youth:

* Secure care -- mandatory detainment for treatment
* Low barrier housing
* Family-centered addiction treatment
* Residential programs
* Day programs
* Alternative school programs
* Concurrent disorders approach
* Supervised injection sites
* Naloxone distribution
* Intersectoral approaches

''Treatment:''

AAP endorses medication-assisted treatment:

* 16 mg is a good starting dose
* Need to counsel patient on sublingual use (keep it under the tongue for five minutes)
* Best to use buprenorphine in combination with naloxone (Suboxone) to prevent injection
* Need to obtain DATA waiver
* More effective in combination with behavioral treatment, important not to use as requirement for retention
* Important to caution against concurrent alcohol and benzo use
* Important to maintain ongoing urine drug screens, including for actual presence of bupe
* Screen for comorbid conditions like Hep C or HIV
* Co-prescribe bupe with OD kits
* Can start to taper around 12-24 months. Look for cues from patient to tell you they are ready.

''Tips:''

* Exude positivity and welcome
* Reduce all barriers to care as much as possible
* Emphasize honesty over perfection
* Motivational interviewing works!
* Contingency management and incentive programs may be helpful too!

Also important to give ongoing mental health assessment and appropriate treatment

(Measured osms) - 2(Na + K)

''Pathophysiology:''

Infection of bone tissue due to either direct inoculation or hematogenous spread.

//Staphylococcus// is the most common organism. Also consider //Pseudomonas// in cases where patient has [[Sickle Cell Disease]].

''Presentation:''

Indolent pain in the bone or [[Cellulitis]] that fails to resolve with appropriate treatment or recurs.

Have high degree of suspicion for infection when a patient has a penetrating wound that you can probe to bone.

''Diagnosis:''

First test is x-ray. Best radiographic test is MRI. Almost never should use tagged WBC scan or bone scan because these can be confounded by overlying skin infections.

Best test is bone biopsy.

''Treatment:''

Unless patient is toxic, surgically debride bone first and biopsy sample before giving antibiotics.

Tailor antibiotic treatment to results of biopsy and treat for 4-6 weeks.

Track response to treatment via ESR or CRP.







Along with soothing baby, research shows that they are [[SIDS]]-protective.

Buy a 1-piece style to avoid choking hazard.

Start after 2 weeks of life to avoid nipple confusion.

Try to wean off of pacifiers by 1-6 months to avoid them from becoming habit-forming.

''Pathophysiology:''

In Parkinson's disease, there is decreased production of dopamine by the Substantia Nigra.

''Presentation:''

* Bradykinesia
* Cogwheel rigidity
* Resting tremor
* Postural/gait instability

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

How old is the patient and are they functional?:

* If old and low-functioning --> [[levodopa]] and [[carbidopa]]
* If young and high-functioning --> [[Dopamine Agonists]]

Adjunctive options:

* Mao-B inhibitors
* COMT inhibitors (-capones)
* Acetylcholine antagonists
* Deep brain stimulation

Aka polycystic ovarian syndrome

''Presentation:''

Obese woman with signs of hyperandrogenism or menstrual irregularities.

Physical exam might show acanthosis nigricans and hirsutism.

''Diagnosis:''

By Rotterdam criteria:

* Oligo/anovulation
* Signs of androgen excess
* Polycystic ovaries (PCO) on ultrasound
* Exclusion of other disorders relating to menstrual irregularity and hyperandrogenism

In adolescents, there must be //persistent// //oligo//menorrhea as anovulation is common, especially in teenagers. PCO morphology should not be used as one of the criteria.

''Treatment:''

First-line is always weight loss

Medical therapy includes [[OCPs|Oral Contraceptive Pills]] for [[AUB|Abnormal Uterine Bleeding]] and metformin for [[metabolic syndrome|Metabolic Syndrome]].

Toothpaste at all ages from birth onward should contain fluoride.






!! Definition

Relief of [[physical|Physical Palliation]], emotional, social, and spiritual suffering in children and their families.

!! Models

The old approach was curative until ineffective than switching to palliative late in the disease course.

New approach is to offer both curative and palliative care simultaneously with the ratio of each discipline shifting with progression of illness.

Other important aspects:

* Multidisciplinary: MD's, NP's, PA's, RN's, therapists, psychologists, SW, child life, teachers, clergy, family, etc
* Not just for those for whom death is imminent
* Should be available outside of the hospital
* Should be available 24-7
* Centered around the child patient and their nuclear family as a unit
** As such, respite and bereavement services are essential
* Not synonymous, but overlapping with [[hospice care|Hospice]]

<<list-links "[tag[Pediatric Superficial Skin Infections]]">>






Or immunizations; or shots

''Principles:''

Vaccinations prime ''active immunity'', which is the kind where the body generates its own antibodies against an antigen. An ''antigen'' targeted by vaccination is usually a pathogenic organism or toxin. Active immunity is maintained by a reservoir of plasma cells that can produce lots of antibodies if they encounter the antigen again in the future.

If a pathogen is already present and there isn't time to generate active immunity, ''passive immunity'' can offer protection instead. Natural passive immunity comes from mother's antibodies that pass across the placenta into baby's blood. This wears off at about 6 months. We can medically administer passive immunity via intravenous immunoglobulins (IVIG).

When the majority of people in a population are vaccinated, they effectively shield those who cannot get vaccinated via ''herd immunity''.

''Reactions:''

A ''normal'' reaction to a shot should not prevent future shots:

* Temp < 104 F
* Erythema
* Pain and consolable crying

An ''abnormal'' reaction contraindicates only future administration of that particular shot:

* Temp >= 104 F
* Inconsolable crying
* Anaphylaxis

Those with an ''egg allergy'' should not get the ''yellow fever'' vaccine. MMRV no longer contains egg products and flu shots shouldn't either but verify to make sure.

Those who are ''immunocompromised'' such as with AIDS, transplant, chemotherapy, or on biologics should not get ''live attenuated'' vaccines. The main one to worry about is ''MMRV''. The old intranasal flu vaccine was live attenuated but the current intramuscular flu is not.

If you are currently sick or have a family history of vaccine reactions, you should still get immunized. There is no solid evidence that vaccines cause ASD.

''Important bits about specific vaccines:''

* [[DTaP]]/[[Tdap]]/Td booster/[[Tetanus]]/[[Diphtheria]]/[[Pertussis]]
* [[MMRV]]/[[Measles]]/[[Mumps]]/[[Rubella]]/[[Varicella|Varicella Zoster Virus]]
* [[Hepatitis B vaccine]]
* [[Hib|H. influenzae]]
* [[HPV]]
* [[Pneumococcal vaccine]]
* [[Meningococcal vaccine|N. meningitidis]]
* [[Rotavirus]]
* [[Flu]]






<<list-links "[tag[Pediatrics]]">>






Can form either in the stomach or the duodenum

''Etiologies:''

* [[H. pylori]]:
** Single ulcer
* NSAIDS :
** Multiple, shallow ulcers
* Malignancy:
** Ulcers with heaped up margins or necrotic
* Curling Ulcer:
** Burn patients
* Cushing Ulcer:
** Associated with increased intracranial pressure, steroid use, or intubation
* [[Gastrinoma]]
** Multiple, refractory ulcers + [[Diarrhea]]

''General Presentation:''

* Gnawing epigastric bleed
* 20% are asymptomatic but come in with complications like GI bleed or anemia
* If improves with food, suggests duodenal ulcer
* If worsens with food, suggests gastric ulcer

''Diagnostic Objectives:''

* EGD with biopsy is gold standard and can help with:
** Need to rule out malignancy
** Need to rule out H. pylori

''Universal Treatment:''

* PPI generally considered best treatment with caveats
* Stop smoking and drinking
* Stop NSAIDS if possible

''Work-Up:''

Signs and symptoms of PUD:

* Perform EGD:
** History and EGD suggest NSAIDS as cause --> Stop NSAIDS and start PPI BID until better, then daily
** NSAIDS not cause --> Look at biopsy results:
*** Biopsy shows malignancy --> Start PPI and staging
*** Biopsy shows H. pylori --> Start triple therapy
*** Biopsy shows simple ulcer --> Start PPI

Focused on symptom management

! Pain:

!! Important Principles:

[img[Table 3 from Korenes Article.png]]

!! Treatment:

Essential to investigate the underlying cause of pain to target your intervention:

* Generic mainstay for moderate to severe pain is opioids
* Neuropathic pain responds best to tricyclics or gabapentin
* Somatic pain responds best to NSAIDS (also sometimes steroids)
* Visceral pain responds best to glucocorticoids or octreotide
* Localized pain can be alleviated by nerve blocks

Also consider complementary therapies








''Movement:''

* Inhibited by ''GABA'':
** Stimulated by ''Ach'':
** Inhibited by ''D2 neurons'':
*** Stimulated by ''Dopamine'':
**** Broken down centrally by COMT and MAO-B
**** Synthesized centrally from ''L-Dopa'':
***** Synthesized in the gut and crosses the BBB into CNS
***** Broken down peripherally by COMT 
***** Also synthesized peripherally into Dopamine, but these molecules cannot cross the BBB into the CNS

Presentation format depends on certainty involved in case.

If you agree with the night float (NF) team and diagnosis is relatively certain, use [[xSOAP format|Daily Spoken Rounds]]:

# S = Hospital Course:
#* ED Dx --> ED intervention --> NF Dx --> NF intervention
#* +/- relevant history
# OAP as normal

If you disagree with NF or diagnosis is relatively uncertain, use [[H&P format|Spoken vs. Written H&P]] + xSOAP:

# Prime team that this will be a little more convoluted because case is more volatile and more information needs to be communicated
# Full spoken H&P with all components from the NF perspective
# S = new information since start of your shift
# OAP from your perspective






Use [[xSOAP format|Daily Spoken Rounds]]:

# S = Hospital Course:
#* Admission dx --> admission intervention
#* If changed, current dx --> current intervention
#* Current trajectory
# OAP as normal






''Precautions:''

* Car safety:
** Rear-facing car seat from birth until ~2yo
** Booster seat until 4'9" tall. Convertible units can switch between rear-facing to forward-facing at appropriate time.
** Seat belt always thereafter
* Child should always wear a fitted helmet
* Guns and chemicals:
** Ideally not present in the home at all.
** If they are present, should be out of reach and in locked storage. In case of guns, ammo should be separately stored from gun.
* Child should never use a trampoline

<<list-links "[tag[Preventable Trauma]]">>






No [[menstrual periods|Menstruation]] by age 15. 

In association, you can diagnose the absence of secondary female characteristics at age 13.

''Differential Diagnosis:''

By presence of visual breasts and uterus on ultrasound:

* Breasts and uterus present:
** Imperforate hymen (confirm by visual inspection)
** Stressor such as weight loss (confirm by history)
** Pregnant before first period arrives (confirm by urine pregnancy test or serum B-hCG)
* Breasts present, but uterus absent:
** [[Mullerian Agenesis]]
** [[Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome]]
* Breasts absent, but uterus present:
** Mass effect on pituitary gland (such as [[Craniopharyngioma]])(confirm with decreased FSH and LH plus Brain MRI)
** [[Kallman Syndrome]] (confirm with presence of anosmia and FSH/LH level)
** [[Turner Syndrome]] (confirm with increased FSH/LH and X,O genotype)
* Breasts and uterus absent:
** Enzymatic deficiencies

Different algorithm focusing on ultrasound/pelvic exam:

* If uterus present --> measure serum FSH:
** If FSH increased -> Peripheral disease --> get karyotype
** If FSH decreased -> central disease --> cranial MRI
* If uterus absent --> get karyotype and measure serum testosterone:
** If 46, XX with normal female levels of testosterone --> [[Mullerian Agenesis]]
** If 46, XY with normal male levels of testosterone --> [[Androgen Insensitivity Syndrome]]

''Common Problems:''

Presentation is ''too long'' and boring because you try to include 100% of the information, don't know how to prioritize, and offer commentary:

* Remember that 60% of the relevant information presented well is better than 100% poorly. Just take us from A to B (60% rule).
* To remediate, learn the [[illness script|Illness Script]] (to help prioritize) and practice out loud and in front of a mirror!

You are very ''nervous'' during your presentation because you are in a new situation, perhaps with an intimidating attending, you're caring too much about the grade, and/or you have imposter syndrome:

* The problem of being new will pass with time.
* Grade grubbing is irrelevant after med school.
* Imposter syndrome is valid, but you got here for a reason, and you are the one who knows your patient best!
* To remediate, practice!

Your presentation is filled with ''"uh's"'' and ''"um's"'' because you fear interruption as might take place in a normal conversation during a pause and/or you're using them as placeholders for thinking:

* This is not a normal conversation. A good team should not interrupt you unless they need to clarify something they heard or you left out something important. You are an orator!
* When you need to think, be silent!
* To remediate, learn illness scripts and practice!

You are ''not engaging'' with your audience on a human level because you want to look at your piece of paper to include 100% of information and you have anxiety:

* To remediate, follow the 60% rule, say the subjective with your head up, say the objective with your head down, and practice!

''The Pager Itself:''

* Takes precedence in [[urgency and importance|Urgent and Important]] when it goes off.
** But the actual content could be anywhere from emergent to routine
* The sound is very anxiety provoking for many people
** Be considerate and silence the pager as quickly as possible

''Etiquette:''

* Try to respond between 30 seconds to 5 minutes after it goes off
* Be ready to move off of your current workspace if need be without losing data
* Do not page someone to your pager, do not page someone to your station, page to your personal number! It is ok to ask others to do the same.
* When answering, slow down and identify yourself as [Dr. Lastname], rank, service
* Want the patient name and room number immediately
** It is ok to interrupt to get this information
** You should wait, even if the other person is not ready for your call

''Urgency:''

* Emergent -  stop everything, give necessary verbal orders, go to patient
* Urgent - give your immediate attention, but stay where you are
* Routine - it can wait until later
* Tell the caller how quickly you will be addressing the task
** Copy down the person who called and record the name for later

Used to treat [[Tuberculosis]]

Consists of rifampin, isoniazid, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol

All can cause hepatotoxicity

Pyrazinamide -- hyperuricemia, gout

Ethambutol -- visual disturbance, optic neuritis

Common cause of diarrhea in young children

''Prophylaxis:''

Oral vaccine available. Need not be give to every child, but can help prevent [[intussusception|Intussusception]].






Or "German measles"

''Pathophysiology:''

Caused by rubella virus

''Presentation:''

Child with prodrome of diffuse, tender lymphadenopathy that progresses to fever //and// rash. Rash will start in face then spread down the trunk and limbs--clearing in a similar manner (just like measles).

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Supportive

''Prophylaxis:''

Prevent with the [[MMRV]] vaccine






Aka spontaneous bacterial peritonitis

''Pathophysiology:''

Usually polymicrobial infection of Strep and Gram-negative rods

''Presentation:''

Asymptomatic -or- fever with abdominal pain

''Diagnosis:''

Paracentesis = >250 polys

''Treatment:''

Ceftriaxone

''Prophylaxis:''

Total protein < 1.0 --> fluoroquinolone






''Presentation:''

Itchy body, specifically in the webs of the hands

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical, or with skin scrapings

''Treatment:''

Permethrin








''Pathophysiology:''

Ring at gastroesophageal junction

''Presentation:''

* "Steakhouse" dysphagia

''Diagnosis:''

* Barium swallow = narrowing at GE junction
* EGD with biopsy = narrowing at GE junction; rule out cancer

''Treatment:''

Lyse the ring during EDG






''Pathophysiology:''

Collagen deposition disorder

''Presentation:''

* [[CREST syndrome]] or [[Systemic Sclerosis]]
* Relentless [[GERD]]

''Diagnosis:''

* Barium swallow = widened lower esophagus
* Manometry = no contraction of lower esophagus
* EGD with biopsy

''Treatment:''








''Pathophysiology:'' 

Synchronous firing of the brain

If this is first-time seizure, consider [[VINDICATE]] mnemonic for etiology

Recurrent seizures --> Epilepsy

''Categorization:''

* Loss of consciousness (LoC):
** Present = ''Complex''
** Absent = ''Simple''
* Coverage of brain/body:
** Whole = ''Generalized''
** Focal = ''Partial''

Simple generalized = Rare, could it be a pseudoseizure?

Complex generalized = Grand mal

Atonic = No LoC, No tone --> Valproate

Myotonic = No LoC, + tone --> Valproate

Absence = + LoC, No loss of tone --> Ethosuximide

''Presentation:''

Can present in numerous different ways but...

Classic generalized convulsive:

* LoC
* Jerking
* Tongue biting
* Bowel/bladder incontinence
* ''Post-ictal state''

''Work Up, Aka "So you have a seizure:"''

Is there a history of epilepsy?:

* Positive history of epilepsy --> Manage and consider other etiologies:
** Check medication levels
** Either increase dose, add drug, or change drugs
** Still consider VINDICATE
* Negative history of epilepsy --> 1st-time seizure; Are they currently seizing?:
** Seizing greater than 5 minutes -or- more than 20 minutes without return to baseline --> Status Epilepticus (keep progressing meds until it stops):
*** Give lots of lorazepam --> fosphenytoin --> midazolam + propofol --> phenobarbital
** Seizures have resolved --> Perform EEG, CT (or MRI), and consider VINDICATE

''Treatment:''

Anti-epileptic drugs ([[AEDs]])






Or herpes zoster

''Pathophysiology:''

After a child gets [[Chicken Pox]], [[Varicella Zoster Virus]] hides in the dorsal root ganglion (DRG). If patient gets immunocompromised, the virus can reactivate.

''Presentation:''

Patient has some sort of immunocompromise (such as age >65yo). Rash is vesicles on erythematous bases in various stages of healing, but limited to dermatomal distribution of affected DRG.

There may be an extremely painful prodrome and the pain can linger past clearance of the rash as post-herpetic neuralgia.

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Supportive, but acyclovir can reduce duration of rash.

Post-herpetic neuralgia can be treated with tricyclic antidepressants, gabapentin, or pregabalin.

''Prophylaxis:''

Prevent chicken pox in children with [[MMRV]].

If child has already had chicken pox, elderly adults can get a shingles vaccine.

Aka Sudden Infant Death Syndrome

Infant dies without any cause identified on autopsy.

''Prevention:''

* Place infant on back to sleep.
* Place infant in separate bed alone. Do not sleep with infant.
** For risk-reduction with parents who insist on sleeping with baby, recommend they use a Nest or DockATot sleeper for baby.
* Smoking cessation.
* [[Pacifiers]]
* Babies should not be given blankets until age 1-year-old. You may use a "sleep sack" instead as an alternative to swaddling.

If at 24-48 hours of life --> [[Failure to Pass Meconium]]

If greater than 2 years old --> [[Constipation]]






Mnemonic for effective goals: specific and measurable, attainable, relevant, time-bound






''Pathophysiology:''

[[Osteoporosis]]

''Presentation:''

* Female greater than 50yo who fell on her coccyx
* Vertebral step-offs present
* Pinpoint tenderness

''Diagnosis:''

* 1st = X-ray
* Best = MRI

''Treatment:''

Surgery

''Follow-up:''

On osteoporosis with DEXA scan and treatment.






Aka SMA

''Pathophysiology:''

Decreased SMN1 gene expression --> no anterior horn cells --> weakness

''Presentation:''

Patients can get hypoglycemic very easily

''Diagnosis:''



''Treatment:''

Nusinersen, most effective in infants






''Pathophysiology:''

Bone spur pinches the nerve

''Presentation:''

* Older than 30
* No recent heavy lifting needed
* "Sciatica"
* Positive straight leg raise test

''Diagnosis:''

* 1st = X-ray
* Best = MRI

''Treatment:''

Can give surgery if desired by patient






''Pathophysiology:''

Narrowing of the canal

''Presentation:''

* Greater than 50 years old
* Pseudoclaudication:
** Positional
** Higher up than expected
** Better hunched over
** Worse when upright

''Diagnosis:''

* 1st = X-ray
* Best = MRI

''Treatment:''

Laminectomy






Both H&P's are shaped by the [[path of clinical reasoning|Intro to the Art of Clinical Reasoning]].

''Written:''

Goal is to be thorough and complete, including [[all important details|Documenting the H&P]].

''Spoken:''

Goal is to be concise, including only relevant details:

# CC
# HPI -- mostly complete according to format above, but still filtered by ddx
# Try and skip any BS that wasn't included in HPI paragraph 2
# Vitals
# Relevant physical exam maneuvers
# Relevant labs and imaging
# One-liner assessment
# Plan








''Pathophysiology:''

Hematogenous or direct inoculation of joint with Staphylococcus.

''Presentation:''

Red, hot, swollen, tender joint. +/- toxic appearance.

''Diagnosis:''

Arthrocentesis shows greater than 50,000 WBC and gram-positive organisms

''Treatment:''

Empiric nafcillin for MSSA

Vancomycin or linezolid for MRSA







<<list-links "[tag[Stomach]]">>






''Pathophysiology:''

Aka a "lazy eye"

''Presentation:''

Intermittent crossing of eyes, asymmetric corneal light reflex, positive deviation on eye cover test

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

* Occlusion therapy with patch or cycloplegic is first-line
* Surgery may be necessary, especially if present at birth
* May be correctable with glasses if there is refraction error






Helpful to explore children and familes' strengths:

* Knowing them helps frame recommendations for intervention and treatment
* Asking about what a child likes can be used when discussing next steps
* Helps track improvement over time






''Pathophysiology:''

Equivalent to a "brain attack"

3 etiologies:

* Ischemic:
** Thrombotic:
*** Such as from atherosclerosis of cerebral vessel
** Embolic:
*** Flicked off from carotid stenosis or Afib-heart
* Hemorrhagic:
** True = intraparenchymal bleed
** But also subarachnoid hemorrhage

''Presentation:''

Patient has focal neurological deficits that localize to the brain:

* ACA:
** Feet and legs
* MCA:
** Arms, hands, face, speech
* PCA:
** Vision
* Basilar or vertebral:
** Syncope
* Cerebellum:
** Ataxia, impaired coordination, or alternating movements

Type of patient varies:

* Vasculopath:
** [[HTN]], [[DM]], [[HLD]], smoker, old
* Embolic risk:
** Afib, Aflutter, false valve
* Young woman with neck pain after trauma (dissection)
* Thunderclap headache (bleed)

''Algorithm aka "So you have someone with a FND and clinical signs of stroke:"''

Perform non-contrast head CT:

* If CT shows brain bleed --> Hemorrhage:
** Control blood pressure
** Consult neurosurgery for coil vs. clip vs. craniotomy
* If CT shows no brain bleed --> Ischemic; give tPA --> Later, get EKG, echocardiogram, and carotid ultrasound:
** If EKG shows Afib or Aflutter --> Give anticoagulation //without// bridge
** If Echo shows thrombus --> Give anticoagulation //with// bridge
** If carotid ultrasound shows stenosis --> Assess severity:
*** If < 70% and no symptoms --> Medical management
*** If > 70% and symptomatic //or// > 80% no matter what --> Surgical management with carotid endarterectomy or stent placement

''Medical Management:''

Acute:

* tPA:
** If no brain bleed and less than 3 hours since last seen normal (4.5 hours for non-diabetics) --> Give it
*** In ICU --> Control blood pressure to less than 180/105
*** Contraindications: bleed anywhere in the body or recent surgery
* Aspirin 325
* Allow permissive hypertension to < 220/120
* Initiate high-potency statins

Chronic:

* Warfarin: 
** Give if patient has Afib/Aflutter or CHADS-VASc > 2
* Antiplatelet therapy:
*# ASA 81
*# ASA + dipyridamole
*# clopidogrel
* Blood Pressure:
** Control with ACE-i or diuretic to < 140/90
* Diabetes:
** Keep A1c to < 7
* Continue high-potency statin

''Summary Order Sheet:''

* Imaging: EKG, echo, carotid u/s
* Meds: ASA and statin
* Vitals: Permissive HTN
* Labs: A1c, TSH, Lipids, CMP, CBC
* Ancillary: ST/OT/PT






Write out the hospital course in understandable language for the patient and share






In a child with a relatively "full skull", significant trauma is needed to tear the bridging veins such as pedestrian struck, motor vehicle accident, or [[abuse|Child Abuse]] (shaken-baby syndrome).

Characterized by loss of consciousness progressing to coma.

Crescent-shaped on CT scan.












''Presentation:''

Primary = chancre.

Secondary = erythema multiforme.

Tertiary = any neurological symptoms

''Diagnosis:''

If concerned for neuro symptoms --> CSF RPR or Ab






''Presentation:''

[[CREST syndrome]] plus involvement of visceral organs like kidneys, heart, lungs, and GI tract.

!! General Principles:

# Dying children often know they are dying, whether or not they are told 
# Children who are not informed of the gravity of their illness feel isolated and alone
# Children, particularly younger ones, give clues through play, drawings, dreams, and reference to friends and family members who have died
# A physician might not be the best person to talk to a child about his or her death, and who the best person might be depends on who has connected with the child and who best fits the needs of the child and family
# Children may benefit from concrete information about the actual physical process of dying
# Some children may not want to talk about dying.

!! Developmental Considerations:

American Academy of Pediatrics. Committee on Psychosocial Aspects of Child and Family Health. The pediatrician and childhood bereavement. Pediatrics. 2000;105;445–447.

Korones DN. Talking to children who are dying: confessions from the trenches. Am Acad Hospice Palliative Med Bull. 2004;5(2)






Aka [[Tetanus]], [[Diphtheria]], and [[Pertussis]] shot for adolescents and adults

Give for first time in adolescence and then q10 years (also ok to use Td booster in subsequent doses).

See [[Tetanus]] for guide on how to handle administration for wounds






''Pathophysiology:''

Muscular

''Presentation:''

Vise-like pressure or tightness in circumferential pattern around the head bilaterally, often radiates to neck

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

NSAIDs or Tylenol






''Pathophys:''

Caused by //C. tetani// infection, usually from a "dirty" puncture wound. 

Dirty wounds are defined as coming from rusty metal or if contaminated with dirt, feces, saliva, etc.

''Presentation:''

Leads to lockjaw, muscle spasm, spastic paralysis, asphyxia, death (1/10 of those infected will die).

''Diagnosis:''

Clinical

''Treatment:''

Intubate and sedate, muscle relaxants for comfort, IV antibiotics (metronidazole).

''Prophylaxis:'' 

Start with [[DTaP]] in childhood (5 times total) and then give [[Tdap]] starting in adolescence (every 10 years). 

''"So you have a patient who's wounded!":''

If patient has ''less than 3 lifetime doses'' of tetanus vaccination --> Is the wound clean or dirty?:

* Clean --> Give Tdap
* Dirty --> Give Tdap and tetanus immunoglobulin (TIg)
* Timing of last vaccine doesn't matter if less than 3 lifetime doses total. Always at least give a new shot.

If patient has ''3 or more lifetime doses'' --> Is the wound clean or dirty?:

* Clean --> When was the last vaccination?:
** Greater than 10 years ago --> Give Tdap
** Less than 10 years ago --> No ppx needed
* Dirty --> When was the last vaccination?:
** Greater than 5 years ago --> Give Tdap
** Less than 5 years ago --> No ppx needed
* TIg is never needed if patient got more than 3 lifetime doses.






''Pathophysiology:''

Associated with [[OCD]] and [[ADHD]]

''Presentation:''

Physical tics, vocal tics, or both are present and consistent in their manifestation

Age is less than 18 at diagnosis. Duration has been greater than 1 year.

Once you have arrived at the ''shortlist'' of possible diagnoses for a patient, you need to decide what therapies to initiate. 

You select each therapy by weighing the ''benefit'' against ''cost''.

Benefit is adjusted by your ''certainty'' for the diagnosis you intend to treat and is measured via the intended therapeutic effect.

Cost is adjusted by the level of ''risk'' associated with a therapeutic and is measured via the side effects.

Certainty and risk are both ''unique'' to the case of each ''individual patient''.

One means of breaking benefit and cost into component parts is the mnemonic ''STEP'' (safety, tolerability, efficacy, and price.

In order to initiate a therapy with ''high risk'', you should have ''high certainty'' for the target diagnosis. If there is low risk, you have a much lower threshold for initiation.

It is ok to treat ''multiple diagnoses'' at once. In fact you can use each ''treatment as a form of diagnostic'' by assessing response to it. If taking this approach, make the therapeutic modality ''aggressive'' so the result will not be ambiguous and make sure your treatments ''do not counteract'' each other.






''Pathophysiology:''

Infection

''Presentation:''

Caribbean farmer with symptoms just like [[Celiac Sprue]] 

''Diagnosis:''

EGD with biopsy = blunted villi

''Treatment:''

Antibiotics






''Presentation:''

Primary infection presents like pneumonia that won't go away empiric treatment.

Secondary infection (reactivation) presents with fever, night sweats, weight loss, and hemoptysis necessitating work-up for lung cancer as well.

Signs of [[meningitis|Meningitis]] or [[pleural effusion|Pleural Effusion]] might also show as well.

''Risk Factors:''

Associated with being homeless, in prison, healthcare workers, immigrants from endemic regions, urban concentration, etc. Don't forget about those who live with carriers!

''Diagnosis:''

Primary will show cavitary lesions (caseating granulomas) on chest x-ray in the middle and lower lobes.

Secondary will show ghon complexes in the apices.

Asymptomatic Screen:

* Perform a PPD (or IFN-y assay):
** IFN-y is equally but more expensive than PPD, however it will not give a false positive for people with BCG vaccine. 
** Ignore the existence of BCG vaccine when following this algorithm using PPD results.
** Thresholds:
*** >= 5 mm in high-risk immunocompromised patients or someone who co-habitates with an infected person
*** >= 10 mm in medium-risk people such as prison population, homeless shelter resident, healthcare worker, or immigrant from endemic country
*** >= 15 mm in low-risk individuals without risk factors
** If PPD is negative --> Stop, Rescreen as necessary (usually annually)
** If PPD is positive --> Patient has been exposed, Get Chest X-Ray:
*** If Chest X-Ray is negative --> Exposure only, Treat with isoniazid (INH) plus B6 for 9 months
*** If Chest X-Ray is positive --> Patient infected, get acid-fast bacilli (AFB smear), around this time get patient into isolation room as well
**** If AFB is negative --> Latent infection, Treat with INH + B6 for 9 months
**** If AFB is positive --> Active infection, Treat with rifampin, INH, pyrazinamide, and ethambutol therapy ([[RIPE|RIPE Therapy]])

In acutely ill patient with signs of TB:

* Do a chest X-ray looking for apical lesions
* No matter what, also get 3 AFB smears (q8 hrs) and 3 cultures (q24 hrs in early morning)
** If AFB and cultures negative --> Work up patient for other disease, such as lung cancer
*** If culture is initially negative, but comes back 6 weeks later as positive --> Patient has non-tubercular mycobacterium infection, Treat with clarithromycin and ethambutol
** If AFB or cultures positive --> Patient has TB, Treat with RIPE therapy

A turkey is a time consuming task that once started does not require much direct attention (e.g. MRI or LP). Start early so that your results are ready in timely fashion).

WIndows of opportunity are times when resources are available because others are not using them. If you have a turkey, try to initiate it during a window of opportunity (e.g. order the MRI during pre-rounds rather after presenting to attending; get consult order when you know the consultant will be arriving at hospital).
