Throughout your whole day, prioritize according to the [[3 D's]].

# ''Pre-Work:''
#* Do this alone/hidden so as not to be disturbed
#* Collect objective info (vitals, labs, documentation) to fill out data tracker and [[to do list|To Do List]]
#* Get hand-off from night float
# ''Resident Rounds:''
#* This is when you are present/visible to the rest of the medical team
#* Collect your subjective info by visiting with patients and speaking with nursing + consultants
#* "Card flip" with the upper level resident where you go over your prospective plans and presentations for rounds
#* Get your orders in (you should put your money on the table before speaking with the attending) and add to your to do list
# ''Hard Stop'' for didactics:
#* You should be present and non-distracted by work that should already be done
# ''Attending Rounds:''
#*Your chance to get feedback on your decision making and presentation
#* Visit with patients again
#* Make changes to the plan
#* Add to to do list
# ''Work Rounds:''
#* Your time to check off the to do list
#* Do procedures
#* Have family meetings
#* Write notes
#* Eat
#* If on-call, try to finish work before time when you will need to see new patients, otherwise, go home!






Or ampicilin/sulbactam






Important tasks are generated by ''you''

Urgent tasks are generated by ''others''

In order to be ''important'', a task should be be directly related to patient care in the realm of the 3 D's:

* Dying (patient safety)
* Diagnosis
* Discharge

''First priority'' tasks are important and urgent:

* Codes and rapid responses
* Discharge orders and forms
* Preparing for procedures by making sure the team is ready and the proper labs have been ordered

''Second priority'' tasks are important:

* Seeing patients
* Generating orders
* Filling out your tracker

''Third priority'' tasks are urgent:

* Clarifying documentation
* Finishing notes
* Signing verbal orders

''Fourth priority'' tasks are neither important nor urgent:

* Facebook/Twitter/Amazon
* Chit-chat
* Eating and sleeping

''Exceptions'' to the hierarchy:

* Interdisciplinary rounds (aka the huddle)
* Relationship deposits -- investing in doing a trivial task for someone else in order to build quid pro quo
* [[Turkeys and Windows]]
* Personal morale boosters used sparingly to get through the day

Learn to say ''"no"'' (aka "later"), if task is not as important as what you are doing, but someone else is treating it as urgent:

* Visibly add it to your to-do list
* Give a reason for not addressing it right away
* Invite person to check back in with you on it at a specific time






* Vertebral anomalies <-- sacral ultrasound
* [[Anus, imperforate|Imperforate Anus]] <-- cross-table x-ray
* Cardiac anomalies <-- echocardiogram
* Tracheoesophageal fistula <--catheter + x-ray
* Esophageal atresia
* Renal anomalies <-- VCUG
* Limb anomalies <--wrist x-ray

!! Important Oxygen Parameters:

* FiO2
* PEEP
* Inspiratory time

!! Important CO2 Parameters:

* Rate
* Tidal volume
* PEEP

!! Important Modes:

* Conventional Mechanical Ventilation:
** Support Mode: Every breath is supported, but spontaneous
** Control Mode: Every breath is made by the vent
*** PRVC (Pressure-regulated volume control)
* SIMV-PRVC + PS (Synchronized intermittent mechanical ventilation):
** Respiratory rate set
** Additional breaths supported
** Things to set (things to report):
*** Tidal volume: 6-8 mL/kg
*** Rate
*** PEEP: At least 6
*** PIP
*** FiO2
* Jet Vent
* Oscillator Vent: Small, but rapid changes in pressure
** Parameters: DeltaP, MAP, frequency, percent inspiratory time
** Worse ventilation
** Decreased pre-load
* Bi-Vent: MAP approximates p-high rather than p-low

First step is to determine which set of symptoms predominate:

* If they experience hearing loss and/or tinnitus --> Peripheral Pathology:
** [[BPPV]]
** [[Labrynthitis/Vestibular Neuritis]]
** [[Meniere's Disease]]
* If they experience brain stem neighborhood signs or focal neurological deficits (often related to cerebellum) --> Central lesion with insult in the posterior fossa, Get MRI:
** [[Multiple Sclerosis]]
** Tumor
** [[CVA]]
** [[Abscess]]
** Complex [[Migraine]]
** [[Seizures]]

<<list-links "[tag[Weakness]]">>






Make sure [[vaccinations|Pediatric Vaccinations]] are up to date.

''Assess growth:''

By means of measuring head circumference, height, and weight. In [[failure to thrive|Failure to Thrive]], first thing to drop is weight, then height, then head.

Coach the parents on [[feeding|Feeding Baby]].

''Assess for [[injury/abuse|Child Abuse]]:''

Red flags are any injury to an infant, suspicious lesions or shapes, big injuries (like [[subdural hematoma|Subdural Hematoma]] or femoral fracture), or failure to thrive.

''Assess [[safety|Preventable Trauma]]:''

Discuss issues like smoking cessation, seat belts/car seats, gun safety, [[swimming|Drowning]], and trampolines.

''Assess [[development|Child Development]]''

''Perform [[exam|Well-Baby Exam]]''

''Anticipatory Guidance:''

Every family should have a thermometer. Babies need a digital rectal thermometer.






''Measurements:''

Weight, length, and head circumference

''Cord:''

If just born, check cord for two arteries and one vein. Make sure it is clamped correctly.

''Shots and drops:''

If just born, administer vitamin K, +/- hepatitis B vaccine, and erythromycin ointment in eyes.

''Examination:''

Scalp -- for hematomas and fontanelles

Eyes -- for red reflex

Mouth -- for cleft lip/palate

Clavicles -- for crepitus indicating fracture

Heart -- for murmurs

Lung -- for abnormal sounds

Cord --  for defects

Hips -- Ortolani and Barlow maneuvers

Genitals -- for gender, defects such as hypo/epispadias, both testicles present if male

Anus -- for imperforation

Skin -- for jaundice

Name: [Title] [Last Name]

Body: At most 2 paragraphs, each with 3 lines

* Make your ask very clear (in just one line)
* Use font with serif so no room for misinterpretation, also big enough enough to read at 10 or 12 size
* Dont use:
** Colors
** Squiggles
** Emojis, animations, gifs
** Abbreviations
** Idioms

* Monday --> Friday --> Wednesday cadence

General Format: [Drug] [Dose] [Route] [Frequency]...[Other]

''Common symbols and abbreviations:''

* a̅ = before (ante)
* bolus = as fast as possible
* c̅ = with (cum)
* Δ = change
* D/C = discontinue, stop
* NPO = absolutely nothing by mouth (nil per os)
* qAC = before meals (ante cibum)
* qDay = every day (default is that first dose will be tomorrow at med pass)
** q24hr is same but more rigid specification for the interval between each dose given, qDay is more flexible
* BID = twice daily
** q12hr
* TID = three times daily
** q8hr
* qHS = at bedtime (quora somni)
* p̅ = after (post)
* PRN for [indication] = as needed for [indication]
* s̅ = without (sine)
* Tabs per dose:
** ~~i~~ = 1 tab
** ~~ii~~ = 2 tabs
** ~~iii~~ = 3 tabs
** ~~iiii~~ = 4 tabs etc
* x̅ = except

''Examples:''

Amlodipine 10mg po qDay...[First dose now]

Fluids: Normal saline 1000 cc IV at 150 cc/hr...[stop p̅ 500 cc]

Glargine 24 units SubQ qHS...[x1 now]
 
Δ Glargine to 30 units [SubQ qHS]

D/C Glargine

''Ordering vitals:''

Recommended default frequencies:

* q1hr in ICU
* q4hr on general floors
* q8hr, q12hr, qShift for skilled nursing or rehab facility
* qDay at nursing home

''Ordering Diet:''

By permissiveness:

* Regular:
** Cardiac
** Diabetic
** Renal
* Soft mechanical
* Pureed
* Solid liquids
* Clears
* NPO x̅ meds
* NPO

''Ordering Labs:''

* CBC:
** ...now
**...in AM
**...c̅ differential
* BMP:
**...now
**qAM...[stat]

''Ordering imaging:''

[Test] for [Indication]

''Ordering consults:''

[Subspecialty] [Individual] for [Indication]
